<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Academy of Science Dismisses AIDS Vaccine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 28 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian Academy of Science
Wednesday dismissed claims by Nigerian surgeon Jeremiah Abalaka to
have produced HIV vaccines, just as the federal government
appointed a committee to verify all claims of cure for HIV/AIDS in
the country.
</P>
<P>
A committee, set up by the academy in April to investigate the
 scientific basis of Abalaka's claims, said in a report released
Tuesday in Lagos, that the preventive and curative vaccines were
not properly tried or evaluated in humans before being made
public, the News Agency of Nigeria reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The vaccines as prepared by Dr. Abalaka appear impure and may
cause hypersensitivity reactions or transmit serious infectious
agents such as hepatitis C, which is another known cause of liver
cancer," the five-man committee chaired by Etim Essien said.
</P>
<P>
In spite of their findings, the committee recommended further
investigation of the claims by Abalaka and others.
</P>
<P>
"We take the position that, despite the fact that the claims as
we have assessed them have extremely weak or sometimes
non-existent scientific basis, all the claims should be
investigated with proper scientific vigor," the committee said.
</P>
<P>
On the same day the report was released, the federal government
set up a 15-member expert/technical committee to verify the claim
by Abalaka and a host of other medical doctors and traditional
healers to have found a cure for the deadly disease.
</P>
<P>
The committee, headed by Idris Mohammed, an immunologist from
the University of Maiduguri Teaching Hospital, has two months to
complete its assignment.
</P>
<P>
Abalaka stunned the medical community last year when he told a
press conference in Abuja that he had developed a curative and
preventive vaccines for HIV, the virus that causes AIDS. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
