<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Cypriots Take Retaliatory Measures Against U.N. Peacekeepers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The breakaway Turkish Cypriot
regime in northern Cyprus announced Thursday to impose restrictions
on the U.N. peacekeepers in retaliation for the U.N. decision to
renew their mandate without asking for its approval.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Peacekeeping Force in Cyprus (UNFICYP) would henceforth
only be allowed to cross to northern Cyprus through a checkpoint at
Ledra Palace in Nicosia and would be required to insure their
vehicles with Turkish Cypriot insurance companies, according to the
decision.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots also revoked free water and electricity
supply to the UNFICYP soldiers, demanding that they pay for the
supply they use in their bases north of the U.N.-monitored buffer
zone on the divided island, local media reported.
</P>
<P>
The measures were taken as a retaliation for the U.N. Security
Council's decision to renew the mandate of the UNFICYP without
considering the Turkish Cypriots' demand for separate consultations
with the U.N. troops.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the measures, UNFICYP spokeswoman Sarah Russell
said the UNFICYP is consulting with the United Nations headquarters
and will respond "in due course."
</P>
<P>
Russell said that so far, the UNFICYP paid "the people in the
north" -- referring to the Turkish Cypriots -- for water and the
government-controlled Cyprus Electricity Authority for electricity.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into the Turkish Cypriots-controlled
north and the Greek Cypriots-dominated south since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed coup seeking union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the UNFICYP, which comprises 1,208 soldiers and 33
civilian police from 12 countries, has been patrolling along the
180-kilometre dividing line separating the two communities.
</P>
<P>
In 1983, the Turkish Cypriots unilaterally declared a
breakaway "Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus," which is only
recognized by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash has been demanding that his
self-declared regime be treated as an equal to the internationally
recognized Cyprus government, which has been rejected by the U.N.
and the government under President Glafcos Clerides. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000629.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran's Reformist Campaign Cannot be Stopped: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Interior Minister Abdolvahed
Mousavi Lari said on Thursday that the reformist campaign fostered
by President Mohammad Khatami cannot be stopped by the
conservatives.
</P>
<P>
The social and cultural reformist movement which started from
President Khatami's presidential election victory in 1997 will
continue its course and eventually bear fruits, Lari told a
gathering of senior provincial officials.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the reformist movement is irreversible despite
impediments that are frequently put on its way by the
conservatives, the Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The minister, a close ally of President Khatami, also criticized
the conservative Guardians Council (GC) for annulling parliamentary
election results in a number of constituencies, blocking the way
for reformers to get control of the parliament.
</P>
<P>
The cancellations were not understandable and for no good
reasons, the minister said, adding that such acts could only cast a
shadow of doubt over the authenticity of the election.
</P>
<P>
President Khatami's reformist allies won a landslide victory in
Iran's sixth parliamentary election held on February 18, ending the
long-time control of the legislative body by the conservatives.
</P>
<P>
Unwilling to accept the humiliating defeat, the conservative
establishment has since taken tough measures to strengthen its rule
and curb the reformist movement.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, the GC, supervisor of the election, has annulled
first-round and runoff election results in some 10 constituencies,
depriving 12 reformist candidates of their right to enter the 290-
seat parliament.
</P>
<P>
Facing severe pressure from the conservatives, the new
parliament, dominated by reformers, managed to start work on May
27. But a number of seats are still vacant due to the GC's
cancellation of election results. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
