<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2000GMT, Thursday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT -- U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan Wednesday night
promised to Lebanese President Emile Lahoud to resolve the alleged
Israeli encroachments on Lebanese border within three days,
Lebanese National News Agency (LNNA) reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Annan promised me to end the violations in three days and to
send radar systems and helicopters to monitor any future Israeli
violations of Lebanon's air space or territorial waters", Lahoud
was quoted as saying. (Lebanon-UN)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- U.S. and British warplanes bombed targets in southern
Iraq on Thursday morning, killing one woman and injuring another.
The hostile planes shelled Rumaillah region in the southern
province of Basra and "led to the martyrdom of one woman and injury
of another," the official Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The report did not say whether Iraqi ground forces confronted
the planes. (Iraq-US-Bombing)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran Wednesday night freed 450 Iraqi prisoners of war
(POWs), 12 years after a bloody war between the two countries
ended.
</P>
<P>
The POWs were released on the border spot of Khosrawi in the
western Kermanshah Province, the Islamic Republic News Agency
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
With the release of this batch of POWs, Iran has freed a total
of 3,389 Iraqi POWs since the beginning of the current Iranian year
(which started March 20), said Asghar Azizi, head of Iran's POW
commission. (Iran-Iraq-POWs)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- The breakaway Turkish Cypriot regime in northern
Cyprus announced Thursday to impose restrictions on the U.N.
peacekeepers in retaliation for the U.N. decision to renew their
mandate without asking for its approval.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Peacekeeping Force in Cyprus (UNFICYP) would henceforth
only be allowed to cross to northern Cyprus through a checkpoint at
Ledra Palace in Nicosia and would be required to insure their
vehicles with Turkish Cypriot insurance companies, according to
thedecision.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots also revoked free water and electricity
supply to the UNFICYP soldiers, demanding that they pay for the
supply they use in their bases north of the U.N.-monitored buffer
zone on the divided island, local media reported. (Cyprus-Northern
Cyprus-UNFICYP) 
</P>
</TEXT>
