<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombian Rebel Proposes Plan To Eradicate Illicit Plants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
According to the FARC plan, the pilot center will be installed
in Cartagena del Chaira, a municipality of 20,000 inhabitants in
the Amazons jungles of the south of Colombia, where the guerrilla
controls the production of cocaine and the laboratories.
</P>
<P>
The FARC proposal was delivered to delegates from Latin America,
Canada, Japan, and Europe, who gathered in this place of the
country to seek non-military solutions for the reduction of the
area cultivated with coca plants, where the biggest harvest of
this drug is produced.
</P>
<P>
The FARC said that "the pilot plan" to eradicate the cultures
must be financed with funds from the Colombian government, the
United States, Germany, France, Italy, and the United Nations,
under the administration of the guerrilla.
</P>
<P>
According to the plan, the FARC will present a report every six
months on the advance of the project to a commission of three
delegates of the Colombian State and to the United States, England,
France, Spain, and the United Nations representatives.
</P>
<P>
The FARC is the largest rebel group in Colombia.
</P>
<P>
U.S. lawmakers this week finalized the 1.3 billion dollar aid
plan. The package aims to help Colombia retake jungles near San
Vicente del Caguan where the FARC and rebel paramilitary groups
guard and tax cocaine-producing plots for huge financial payoffs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
