<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil, Mexico, First Choice for Investors in L.America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Mexico and Brazil are better
markets for Latin American investors, according to the results of
a poll made by the Salomon Smith Barney investment bank, the "El
Mercurio" Chilean daily reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
This credit institution made the poll among those who attended
its 8th Annual Conference on Latin America held in New York last
week. Most of the people asked were institutional investors from
the United States and abroad.
</P>
<P>
The poll said that 55.2 percent of the investors consider
Brazil their favorite market, followed by Mexico, with 41.4
percent.
</P>
<P>
Argentina was the country most frequently mentioned as the last
in the preferences within the market averages, or "underweight,"
with 74.1 percent of the answers, followed by Chile with 59.3
percent, and Venezuela and Peru with 55.6 percent each.
</P>
<P>
Each of the questions made in the poll was answered by an
average that varied between 28 and 33 investors.
</P>
<P>
The sampling included 24 questions, among them the amount in
percentage of their investments in the various countries, shares,
sectors more and less frequently chosen, and the future actions of
the U.S. Federal Reserve. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
