<HEADLINE> US China Experts Urge Clinton to Delay Decision on Building NMD </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Current plans for NMD deployment are likely to serve as a
catalyst for China to accelerate nuclear weapons modernization,
since it believes that even a simple missile defense configuration
will leave its nuclear arsenal vulnerable," they said.
</P>
<P>
"A deployment decision at this time may also make U.S.
cooperation with China on a range of issues more difficult,
particularly with respect to Taiwan and regional security
questions.
</P>
<P>
"In addition, the U.S. plans to expand trade and economic
relations with China would be adversely affected by a precipitous
NMD deployment decision," the China experts added.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said Wednesday that he would make a decision on whether
to begin building the NMD "sometime over the next several weeks"
after the third test of the system on July 7.
</P>
<P>
The international community has opposed the NMD, which would
either breach or require major changes to the 1972 Anti-Ballistic
Missile Treaty between the United States and the then Soviet Union,
a cornerstone of arms control.
</P>
<P>
Arms control experts said the U.S. plan to set up the NMD
system runs against the trend of the times and will have a major
adverse impact on global and regional strategic balances and
stability. 
</P>
</TEXT>
