<HEADLINE> Syria's Ruling Party Calls for Building New Arab Order </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The Ninth Congress of Syria's
ruling Arab Socialist Baath Party has urged for the establishment
of a new Arab order to "serve the higher Arab national interests."
</P>
<P>
"The Arab revival needs effective solidarity and joint action to
build a new Arab order the groups all the Arab countries, respects
the interests of each country and serves the higher Arab national
interests," a statement of the congress said.
</P>
<P>
According to the official SANA news agency Thursday, the Baath
congress, held from June 17-20, discussed the developments of the
Arab situation.
</P>
<P>
It called for following up the cooperation between Syria and
Egypt on the one hand and member states of the Gulf Cooperation
Council (GCC) on the other in the framework of the Damascus
Declaration.
</P>
<P>
The declaration was signed in March 1991 by foreign ministers of
Syria, Egypt and six Gulf Arab states -- Kuwait, Saudi Arabia,
Oman, the United Arab Emirates, Bahrain and Qatar, to strengthen
their cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The Baath congress underscored the importance of tuning the
declaration into a nucleus of a strong well-established and
comprehensive cooperation ties in all fields, according to the
statement.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the congress highlighted the desire to strengthen
Syria's ties with Lebanon, Jordan, Yemen, as well as the other Arab
countries.
</P>
<P>
It also emphasized the importance of Syria's ties with
neighboring Arab and Islamic countries, particularly Iran and
Turkey, to contribute to the development of neighborly ties and
common interests. 
</P>
