<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Capital to Hold Parliamentary Runoff Election Friday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 29 (Xinhua) -- A runoff election for the sixth
Majlis (parliament) of Iran will be held on Friday in the Tehran
constituency, in which four candidates will run for two seats in
the 290-member legislative body.
</P>
<P>
The week-long election campaign by the hopefuls ended Thursday
and the poll will start at 09:00 local time (0430 GMT) Friday, the
Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
According to the election headquarters at the Interior Ministry,
the vote casting in some 2,124 ballot boxes will last 10 hours and
could be extended for two hours if required. The result is to be
announced within a maximum of 24 hours after the end of the
polling.
</P>
<P>
Citizens of the Tehran constituency had voted in 30 candidates
in the first-round election held on February 18, of which 29 were
reformists supporting President Mohammad Khatami's moderate
policies.
</P>
<P>
But the conservative Guardians Council (GC), supervisor of the
elections, said there had been riggings in the election process and
nullified more than 700,000 votes.
</P>
<P>
After a three-month delay, the council finally confirmed 28
winners in the constituency, ordering the other two seats to be
decided in a runoff. Among the 28 winners confirmed, only two were
from the conservative camp, including former president and Majlis
speaker Hashemi Rafsanjani.
</P>
<P>
The two were believed to have entered the winners' list with the
help from the powerful GC. Amid strong protests from reformists,
Rafsanjani announced that he would not take his seat in the Majlis.
His substitute is to be elected through a by-election.
</P>
<P>
The February 18 election resulted in a landslide victory for
reformists, putting end to the long conservative dominance in the
legislative body.
</P>
<P>
However, the conservatives still control most of the country's
powerful state organs like the police and the judiciary.
</P>
<P>
After severe struggle with the conservative establishment, the
new Majlis started work on May 27.
</P>
<P>
But a number of seats are still vacant due to the GC's partial
annulling of election results. The conservative body is said to
have cancelled first-round and runoff election results in 10
constituencies, involving 12 candidates, all belonging to the
reformist camp. 
</P>
</TEXT>
