<HEADLINE> Annan Promises Lebanon to Resolve Israeli Violations in 3 Days </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 29 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan
Wednesday night promised to Lebanese President Emile Lahoud to
resolve the alleged Israeli encroachments on Lebanese border within
three days, Lebanese National News Agency (LNNA) reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Annan promised me to end the violations in three days and to
send radar systems and helicopters to monitor any future Israeli
violations of Lebanon's air space or territorial waters", Lahoud
was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Lahoud added that Annan, in his phone conversation with Lahoud,
was "unequivocal in admitting that Israel is violating the Lebanese
border and expressed admiration of Lebanon's stance."
</P>
<P>
Lahoud said Annan asserted "absolute confidence" that the
Israelis would definitely withdraw from the violated border
locations despite their current procrastination tactics.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon accused Israel of still occupying 16 points of its
border, after the U.N. has verified the Israeli total withdrawal
from south Lebanon last month. Lebanon is also dissatisfied with
the "blue line" (the U.N.-marked line of the Israeli withdrawal),
saying it does not accord with the international recognized border
between Lebanon and Israel.
</P>
<P>
Two Israeli warplanes violated Lebanese skies by flying over
Beirut Thursday noon.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian- and Syrian-backed Hezbollah group said on Wednesday
that time was running out for ending Israel's border violations
through diplomacy, warning that military reprisals could not be
ruled out.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah's Secretary-General Hassan Nasrallah said in an
interview carried by local newspaper As Safir Wednesday that he had
ordered his guerrillas in south Lebanon to "cease firing until
further notice".
</P>
<P>
Over the future of Lebanese-Syrian relations under the new
Syrian leadership, Lahoud said that the full coordination and
cooperation between the two countries in late Syrian President
Hafez al-Assad's lifetime will be continued under his son, Bashar
al-Assad, who is expected to be the new Syrian president.
</P>
<P>
Bashar was "fully committed to his father's policies, especially
to what concerns full support to Lebanon in all fields," Lahoud
said. 
</P>
