<HEADLINE> Sao Tome's Ex-Ambassador to Portugal to Run for Presidency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, June 29 (Xinhua) -- A former ambassador of Sao Tome, a
west African country, will run for presidency as independent
candidate in the coming general elections scheduled for the first
half of 2001, said reports reaching here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The former ambassador to Portugal Carlos Tiny said in a
declaration that he will formalize his candidature in October, one
month after his return to homeland from Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
Carlos, who served in Lisbon from 1986 to 1988, has been
working as the representative of the World Health Organization to
Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
Tiny said in his declaration that "the trajectory of my life,
my experience in the national politics and the international
issues will help me take up the challenge", adding that his
participation in the campaign is aimed to improve the living
conditions of the population of Sao Tome and Principe.
</P>
<P>
According to the 1990 constitution of Sao Tome and Principe, an
 archipelago country with the population of 128,000, the president
was elected through universal suffrage and has a five-year
mandate. 
