<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Ugandans Come out to Choose Political  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Dozens of voters Thursday morning
lined up at a polling station at the Railway Zone in the Ugandan
capital Kampala, quietly waiting for their turn to get ballot
papers on which there are a " Bus" and a "Dove", symbols for the
Movement and the Multi-party respectively.
</P>
<P>
The Constitution requires that a national referendum be held on
Thursday for Ugandans to determine which of the two systems, the
Multi-party System or the Movement System, will be adopted by the
east African country.
</P>
<P>
Some 10 Million of registered voters went to 16,500 polling
stations on Thursday across the country.
</P>
<P>
In Kampala District, a total of 498,510 registered voters are
expected to vote at more than 1,000 polling stations, according to
the voters' registration list issued by the National Electoral
Commission.
</P>
<P>
"I vote for the Movement System, for the National Resistance
Movement has achieved positive performance in economic and social
sectors since it came to power in 1986," said the 20-year-old
Kalungi Isa.
</P>
<P>
Isa reported his identification in the voters' roll and get a
ballot paper at one of the four tables. Moving to the second,
about 10 meters away from the first, he ducked himself in the
basin on the table and fixed a tick. After putting his vote in the
ballot box on the third table, he had his thumb dipped into
indelible ink on the fourth table, indicating he has cast his vote
and will never be allowed to vote again.
</P>
<P>
"I was born in 1972. The economy of the country was worsening
before the Movement took over the power. I have seen the country
moving forward in various sectors under the Movement
administration," said Nbasa Julius, a graduate of the
country-known University of Makerere.
</P>
<P>
The Market Street at the downtown which is usually busy and
bustling appeared quiet. A dozen of voters were moving toward the
ballot table. One middle-age woman said after casting her vote, "I
prefer the Movement System. If the Multi-party System is adopted,
the country would be divided."
</P>
<P>
After the Movement took over power in 1986, a majority of
Ugandans preferred the Movement while some people wanted a
multi-party system. The idea of holding a referendum to decide
future political system is contained in the constitution which
recognizes people's sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
A 53-year-old man, who cast his vote for the Multi-party System
at 7:30 this morning, said, "This is an unfair contest. Opposition
parties in this country have boycotted the referendum, and many
supporters of the Multi- party have not come out to vote."
</P>
<P>
"The country should adopt the Multi-party System which could
put different views from various parties into the policies of the
government," said the man. "The Movement System is a dictatorship.
Although the Movement is said non-partisan, it will become a party
in future, maybe in 2001," he argued.
</P>
<P>
Paul Ssemogerere, the opposition Democratic Party chief, has
urged Ugandans to boycott the referendum, saying that the
referendum has been rigged and the results are already known.
</P>
<P>
"The Multi-party System is good, but it is not mature for the
country to adopt this political system," said the middle-age
Kahumuza Hannington. "The opposition parties in the country are
weak, and there are no strong leaders, " he added.
</P>
<P>
"The votes for the Multi-party System are estimated at 15 or 25
percent of the total. Most of Ugandans trust the Movement,
because of its administration the country has made great progress
in various fields, including education, health, economy,
infrastructure and agriculture," said Kariisa Richard, a student
of Social Sciences Department of the Makerere University.
</P>
<P>
"The whole day polling exercise ended at five (local time), and
every thing has been going on smoothly," Kick Kizito, public
relations officer of the National Electoral Commission, told
Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
"I have heard no disruption or violence at any polling station
across the country," Kizito added.
</P>
<P>
The results will come out within 48 hours from the close of
final polling in the referendum, according to the National
Electoral Commission. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
