<DOCNO> XIE20000629.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Biggest City Still Paralyzed by Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's commercial capital Lagos
still remained paralyzed on Thursday with hundreds of schools,
hospitals and even mortuaries closed, as the strike by government
workers entered its seventh day.
</P>
<P>
The Lagos state government has ordered the immediate mass
burial of about 600 bodies which have been lying unclaimed in the
city's mortuaries due to the strike.
</P>
<P>
A Lagos State government spokesman said the mass burial was not
an attempt to break the strike.
</P>
<P>
"It is a question of stopping a health hazard," said Segun
Ayobolu on Thursday here.
</P>
<P>
Rubbish has also been piling up on the streets and patients
turned out of hospitals. Some hospitals union militants have
chased out doctors and nurses, according to newspaper reports.
</P>
<P>
One newspaper is warning of the threat of an epidemic looming
from the uncleared piles of rubbish in some areas in the city.
</P>
<P>
They are demanding payment of a minimum monthly wage of 7,500
naira (75 U.S. dollars), the amount for the federal workers, in
stead of 5,000 naira for state governmental employees.
</P>
<P>
So far, the Lagos state government has not indicated to satisfy
their demand, saying that the state is in shortage of fund.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
