<DOCNO> XIE20000629.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Hostages in S. Leone to Be Freed: Liberia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The Liberian government has
announced that more than 200 U.N. peacekeeping troops still being
held hostage by Sierra Leonean rebels are about to be released.
</P>
<P>
The British Broadcast Corporation (BBC) Thursday quoted the
Liberian Information Minister Joe Mulbah as saying in Freetown
that the U.N. peacekeepers, some of whom are Indians, should be
released by this weekend.
</P>
<P>
Liberia is the main backer of rebels of Sierra Leone's
Revolutionary United Front (RUF), and has already obtained the
release of hundreds of U.N. personnel taken hostage by the rebels.
</P>
<P>
The information minister said Liberian President Charles Taylor
had recently received envoys from the United Nations and India and
was asked to solve the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Mulbah said the imminent release of the remaining peacekeepers
was part of a deal under which the Sierra Leonean rebels have been
promised a ceasefire and a return to the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
The RUF rebels originally took hostage about 500 U.N.
peacekeepers in May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
