<DOCNO> XIE20000629.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Disturbances in Zimbabwe After Weekend Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean Police Spokesman Wayne
Bvudzijena said Thursday that disturbances related to the weekend
election results were reported in Chitungwiza and some suburbs in
Harare.
</P>
<P>
Bvudzijena said in a statement that 12 people were arrested and
one vehicle was burnt in connection with the political
disturbances.
</P>
<P>
"We are taking immediate action to forcefully deal with these
situations of political violence and any that might arise," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said Zimbabweans should take heed of police commissioner
Augustine Chihuri's warning last week that violence of any form
would not be tolerated.
</P>
<P>
He said political parties should strongly warn their members
not to indulge or involve themselves in political violence.
</P>
<P>
President Robert Mugabe's Zanu-pf won 62 seats in the weekend
parliamentary elections, followed by the opposition Movement for
Democratic Change (MDC), which got 57 seats. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
