<DOCNO> XIE20000629.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nile Riparian States Urged to Promote Cooperation Over Water Resources Utilization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The 8th Nile 2002 Conference
concluded here Thursday by recommending concrete actions to foster
cooperation among the Nile riparian states.
</P>
<P>
Ahmed Mohammed Hagos, chairperson of the organizing committee,
said that the participants had "very active discussions", and
described the conference as successful.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopian Minister of Agriculture Mengistu Huluka said that
Ethiopia needs all available resources to face the challenges
posed by recurrent drought.
</P>
<P>
"We are gearing our policy more toward irrigation development
in order to secure food self-sufficiency in the future," Mengistu
said.
</P>
<P>
Nile 2002 is a series of conferences during the period from
1993 to 2002 on Nile water issues.
</P>
<P>
The 6,500-km-long Nile, which is one of the longest rivers in
the world, runs across 10 countries, including Egypt, Sudan,
Ethiopia, Eritrea, Kenya, Tanzania, Uganda, Rwanda, Burundi and
the Democratic Republic of the Congo.
</P>
<P>
The 10 countries are expected to reach an agreement over a
comprehensive cooperation on the utilization and distribution of
the Nile River by 2002.
</P>
<P>
Sponsored by the Canadian International Development Agency, the
World Bank, the United Nations Development Program, the U.N. Food
and Agriculture Organization, this year's conference focused on
the promotion of sustainable development and management of the
Nile and poverty alleviation in the region.
</P>
<P>
Some 400 people, including government officials from nine
countries of the Nile Basin Initiative, non-governmental
organizations, international bodies, diplomats, the private sector
and academics, participated in the four-day meeting that began on
June 26.
</P>
<P>
Many participants underscored the need for practical measures
to implement them, stressing the riparian states should move from
consultation
to implementation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
