<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek, Turkish Cypriot Parties Meet to Promote Understanding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Greek and Turkish Cypriot parties
Thursday held a meeting in the U.N.-controlled buffer zone in
Nicosia to promote communication and the spirit of understanding
between the island's two communities.
</P>
<P>
According to Cyprus News Agency, representatives from five Greek
Cypriot parties and four Turkish Cypriot parties attend the meeting
at the Ledra Palace hotel, which was organized by the embassy of
the Slovak Republic in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The participants decided to organize a "festival of mutual
understanding" between the two communities in September at the
Ledra Palace, said a communique. A coordinating committee will be
set up to deal with details of the festival.
</P>
<P>
The communique said the parties, in a cordial and constructive
atmosphere, continued an exchange of ideas on certain practical
issues of contacts between the two communities as well as of views
on the various aspects of the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek and Turkish Cypriot
communities since 1974 when Turkey invaded and occupied the
northern third of the island after a failed pro-Athens coup in
Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations has been trying for years to bring the two
sides back together in a bizonal, bicommunal federation formula,
but little progress has so far achieved.
</P>
<P>
In recent months the Slovak embassy here has organized regular
meetings at the Ledra Palace hotel between party leaders from the
two sides. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
