<DOCNO> XIE20000629.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish President Calls for Constitutional Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Turkish President Ahmet Necdet Sezer
on Thursday called for constitutional reforms to promote the rule
of law so as to better accommodate international conventions, the
Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a seminar on "Constitutional Reform in Turkey:
Principles and Results", Sezer urged constitutional reforms so as
to preserve human rights and freedom in the country in accordance
with universal standards.
</P>
<P>
The current Turkish Constitution was adopted in 1982, in a
period of military rule following a coup in September, 1980. This
constitution replaced the Constitution of 1961, which was also
drafted following a military coup.
</P>
<P>
However, under the 1961 Constitution, a system of checks and
balances had limited the authority of the government, the power of
the president was curtailed, and individual rights and liberties
were given greater emphasis, the president said.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, the 1982 Constitution expands the authority of the
president and restricts the exercise of individual and
associational rights.
</P>
<P>
The European Union has been urging Turkey, which is striving for
the EU membership, to improve human rights conditions to meet the
Copenhagen criteria required by the EU of its full members.
</P>
<P>
Sezer, the former presiding judge of the Constitutional Court,
has vowed to modify the 1982 Constitution in a bid to speed up the
country's accession process to the European club.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that some articles of the 1982 Constitution which
are in conflict with the rule of law, democracy, basic rights and
freedoms should be modified.
</P>
<P>
He expressed optimism that such initiatives will be supported. "
I think that such a conference will be effective in making our
constitution emphasize freedom and spread the democratic culture,"
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
