<DOCNO> XIE20000629.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hundreds Feared Dead in Ferry Accident in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 29 (Xinhua) -- A ship carrying hundreds of
refugees sank in Sahu waters in Indonesia's North Sulawesi on
Thursday afternoon and it was not clear whether anyone had
survived, according to reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The reports quoted Indonesian officials as saying that the
ferry was built to hold 200 passengers but around 500 were
believed to have been aboard after 290 Maluku refugees fought
their way on to the ship on the Halmahera island, North Maluku,
scene of bloody communal clashes this month.
</P>
<P>
The ship left Tobelo on Halmahera en route to Manado, capital
of North Sulawesi. The ship sank about 64 kilometers off the North
Sulawesi coast, about 1,365 kilometers northeast of Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that rescuers suspended the search for
survivors as night fell on Thursday because they lacked proper
equipment to continue.
</P>
<P>
Fog and bad weather had hampered the search during daylight
hours, the reports added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
