<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Health Ministers Adopt New Anti-Tobacco Rules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) health
ministers adopted Thursday a more strict anti-tobacco proposal,
which introduces new anti-smoking labeling rules and a cutting of
the maximum amount of tar and nicotine.
</P>
<P>
EU Commissioner for health and consumer protection David Byrne
said he was very pleased to see the proposal has received strong
support from both the EU ministerial meeting and the European
Parliament.
</P>
<P>
"I am convinced that one of the major health challenges of the
new millennium is to reduce the appalling and entirely preventable
death toll from smoking," he said and called the agreement reached
in Luxembourg "an important step forward."
</P>
<P>
The proposal, now going back to the European Parliament for
final ratification, could force companies to print health warnings
covering almost half of a pack of cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
It will also force cigarette makers to reduce the amount of tar
and nicotine in cigarette. The maximum amount of tar per
cigarette was cut from 12 to 10 milligrams, while the maximum
amount of nicotine to 1 milligrams and carbon monoxide 10
milligrams.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the agreement introduces a prohibition of misleading
claims such as "light," "low tar" and "mild".
</P>
<P>
The health ministers agreed those measures should apply to all
products including that to be consumed in third countries so that
smokers in those countries should not be exposed to tobacco
products which do not meet the EU standards.
</P>
<P>
Over 500,000 EU citizens die of smoking-related disease every
year, and more than 85 percent of new smokers of EU start smoking
before the age of 18. 
</P>
</TEXT>
