<HEADLINE> Ten More Bodies of Boat Tragedy in SW China Recovered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Ten more bodies from the boat
tragedy which occurred at the upper reaches of the Yangtze River
last week were recovered today, bringing the death toll to 113.
</P>
<P>
Local officials said another 17 bodies are still missing.
</P>
<P>
Chen Weiguo, Magistrate of Hejiang County, said the local
government has arranged to provide financial assistance to an
elderly woman and six orphans who lost family members in the
accident.
</P>
<P>
According to the compensation agreement, 80-year old Chen
Yongtai and her orphaned 14-year-old grandchild Chen Tao will be
supported by the village committee.
</P>
<P>
The local government will give a certain sum to people who are
willing to adopt the other five orphans. They are now under the
care of the local civil affairs offices.
</P>
<P>
The local government will try to provide the seven with proper
housing, basic daily life needs, and education for the children.
</P>
<P>
The passenger vessel Rong Jian, which had a maximum holding
capacity of 101 people, was carrying 221 passengers June 22 when
it hit a rock and sank while sailing in foggy conditions. The
ferry was on a stretch of the river near Hejiang, in southwest
China's Sichuan Province. 
</P>
