<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Ranks 146th on UNDP Human Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh ranked 146th among 174
countries in the Human Development Index (HDI) report of the
United Nations Development Program released here Thursday, with an
improvement by 5 percent to 0.461 from 0.440 in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The HDI ranking of Bangladesh among 174 countries has also
improved by 4 to 146 from 150. But the country rates lowest among
the South Asian countries, among which Sri Lanka ranks the highest
(84), followed by Maldives (89), India (128), Pakistan (135),
Bhutan (142) and Nepal (144).
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the launching of the report, State Minister for
Planning Muhiuddin Khan Alamgir said this year's report has
combined human rights with human development for freedom and
solidarity.
</P>
<P>
Reviewing the report, economist Debapriya Bhattacharya said the
country's HDI ranking was better than GDP ranking in the last
report.
</P>
<P>
He said the report made three references on Bangladesh - good,
bad and ugly.
</P>
<P>
The good one is that Bangladesh stands among the 25 countries
whose export growth average more than 10 percent annually. The bad
is serious inability of the court to provide timely remedy.
Bhattacharya observed domestic violence against women was referred
as "ugly" in the report.
</P>
<P>
He urged conscious citizens to exercise vigilance, articulate
priorities, monitor the activities of those who exercise
governmental powers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
