<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan and U.S. Start Project to Help Health Care in Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The United States and Japan
under the name of population and health initiative of the US-Japan
common agenda, started a project Thursday in Cambodia to promote
health care in this country.
</P>
<P>
The team known as "a joint U.S. and Japan project formulation
mission on population and health" visited Cambodia from June 18,
2000.
</P>
<P>
The project will focus on HIV/AIDS, tuberculosis, malaria,
maternal and child health.
</P>
<P>
The HIV/AIDS epidemic is rapidly growing in Cambodia and the
government's anti-AIDS authority claims approximately 180,000
persons (approximately 3.7 percent of adults aged 15-49) have been
infected by HIV/AIDS.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Japan will actively seek ways to implement joint,
parallel or complementary activities, in support of the Royal
Government of Cambodia's national strategies, in an appropriate
and feasible time frame, said Kinichi Komano, director of research
and programming division of Japan's foreign ministry.
</P>
<P>
Tuberculosis is also in its highlight in Cambodia, claiming 10,
000 lives per year. Meanwhile, malaria continues to be a serious
threat to the health of Cambodians, especially women, children and
workers in forested regions, according to a statement released by
the team.
</P>
<P>
The project was initiated by the U.S. President Bill Clinton
and Japanese Foreign Minister Kiichi Miyazawa in 1993, the team
official said.
</P>
<P>
So far, the project has been carried out in Zambia and
Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
He said Cambodia was chosen as the third country to implement
the project because of the situation of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
