<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chirac Stresses Relations Between Development, Human Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 29 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac said
Thursday that there exists a direct link between economic and
social development and human rights and that he indirectly
criticized some Western countries for imposing their doctrines on
others.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with the United Nations Development Program (
UNDP) administrator Mark Malloch Brown at the Elysee presidential
palace, Chirac praised the UNDP for adopting a "pedagogical
approach" rather than one of simple criticism and condemnation
toward developing countries.
</P>
<P>
"There exists a direct link between democracy, freedom, good
government and development. The problem is not simply to impose a
culture concerning human rights on developing countries, but is to
explain to them the relations between development and human rights,
" said Chirac.
</P>
<P>
Chirac said France will continue to support the United Nations
in its efforts to help developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Terming the present aid volume provided by rich countries to
poor countries as "very insufficient," he said developed countries
should fulfill their 20-year-old promise to use at least 0.7
percent of their gross domestic product in aid programs for
developing countries.
</P>
<P>
The UNDP administrator on Thursday presented the French
president with an annual report on development around the world,
with its contents focusing on both development and human rights.
</P>
<P>
France refused to sign a declaration on the universal value of
democracy at an international conference on the subject held in
Warsaw early this week, reportedly because Paris did not wish to
see the conception of democracy be used as a political tool by
some people to interfere into others' internal affairs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000629.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Toughens Mop-up As Chasing Dispersed Rebels in Chechnya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
MOSCOW, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Russian troops have strengthened
the searching of residential areas in Chechnya after the rebels
were surrounded and dispersed near the village of Serzhen-Yurt in
the south party of the war-torn republic this week, Russia news
agencies reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Individual rebel groups are trying to break through the
federal encirclement near the villages of Dzhugurty, Sayasan and
Ersenoi after sustaining heavy losses in the four-day bloody
battle near Serzhen-Yurt, Interfax cited the press center for
Russia's Combined Forces in Chechnya as saying.
</P>
<P>
The federal units killed more than 80 rebels and wounded
scores of the others in the fighting at a price of 12 dead and
dozens of injuries, said the press center.
</P>
<P>
The activities of illegal armed formations have also been
uncovered near the populated areas of Alleroi, Elistanzhi,
Selmentauzen and Makhkety, it said, adding that federal artillery
and air forces have been attacking the discovered rebel
concentrations and their bases.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Russian troops and special police units are mopping
up other parts of the battered republic, where rebels' activities
are reported.
</P>
<P>
They have completely surrounded the village of Stariye Atagi,
a 15,000-resident town 20 kilometers south of Grozny, early
Thursday, as part of a new round of specially-targeted tasks, Itar-
Tass quoted Russian military sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
During the first mop-up of Stariye Atagi at the beginning of
this year, 80 people were held on suspicions of their involvement
in illegal armed formations with some arms seized, the sources
said.
</P>
<P>
Lately, Russian forces have conducted a series of mopping-up
operations in a number of other communities, including Alkhazurovo,
Duba-Yurt and Serzhen-Yurt, eliminating scores of militants and
mercenaries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
