<HEADLINE> LA Lakers Waive Ironman Green </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Ironman A.C. Green was waived
by the Los Angeles Lakers on Wednesday after he won two
championship rings with the franchise in the 1980s and returned to
earn another this month.
</P>
<P>
Green, 36, who ran his league record for consecutive games to 1,
133 this season, averaged 5.0 points, 5.9 rebounds and 23.5
minutes. In the playoffs, he averaged 3.9 points and 4.2 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
"A.C. Green played an important role in helping us win the NBA
championship and has obviously meant a lot to this franchise over
the years," said Lakers Executive Vice President Jerry West.
</P>
<P>
The Lakers re-acquired Green, who was on their "showtime"
championship teams in 1986 and 1987, from Dallas in exchange for
Sean Rooks last September. Green has been in the league for 15
seasons. He played for Phoenix after leaving the Lakers in 1993.
</P>
<P>
He last missed a game on November 18, 1986, when then-Lakers
coach Pat Riley did not play him in Dallas. The previous mark for
consecutive games was 906 by Randy Smith. 
</P>
</TEXT>
