<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Angry About News Coverage Incident in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Turkish officials have reacted
vehemently to an incident in which the U.S. authorities barred a
Turkish reporter from covering a meeting between U.S. Vice
President Al Gore and opponents of the Iraqi government in
Washington on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Deniz Arslan, resident correspondent of the Turkish national
news agency Anatolia in Washington, was not permitted to take
photos of a meeting between Al Gore and opponents of the Iraqi
government even though she was the only Turkish journalist who
would take pictures to be used in the Turkish press at home.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister Cumhur Ersumer said, "no one can impose
embargo on journalists. It is not possible to accept such an
attitude."
</P>
<P>
"We expect the U.S. to explain this attitude," he declared.
</P>
<P>
Aydin Tumen, Acting Chairman of the ruling Democratic Left Party
(DSP), described the incident as an extremely distressing
development, saying "if this incident occurred because they think
Anatolia News Agency is a state institution, it is much more
distressing."
</P>
<P>
Ismail Kose, Acting Chairman of the ruling Nationalist Movement
Party (MHP), said "The Foreign Ministry should launch an
initiative. This incident revealed that the U.S. which brings up
the issue of human rights and press freedom on every occasion to
Turkey did not conform to press freedom."
</P>
<P>
The Chairman of the Turkish Journalists Association, Nali
Gureli, also criticized the U.S. officials for not permitting Deniz
Arslan to take pictures from the meeting, stressing "it is wrong to
assume an unequal treatment among the press organs in an event
aimed at informing the public."
</P>
<P>
"Such a treatment is an expression of negligence and
irresponsibility toward the right to inform the public. It cannot
suit universal concept of free flow of information," he said.
</P>
<P>
Nazmi Bilgin, Chairman of Journalists' Society, described the
incident as a shameful covered racism.
</P>
<P>
"Journalism is a universal occupation. Journalists' freedom to
cover events and inform the public cannot be restricted in any part
of the world," Bilgin said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, addressing a weekly press conference, the Deputy
Spokesman of the Foreign Ministry, Huseyin Dirioz, said they are
following the developments.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the meeting at the U.S. State Department, all
journalists were asked about their nationalities and work places.
Bodyguards of Al Gore did not allow Arslan, the only Turkish
journalist and the Anatolia correspondent in Washington, to enter
the meeting room without any pretext.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the U.S. had done its utmost to bring Iraqi
opposition together in an attempt to topple the legal Iraqi
government under President Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
Turkey is known to be lukewarm to the U.S. maneuver for fear
that instability should arise afterwards. In its Iraq policy, the
Turkish government has given priority to secure stability and the
territorial integrity of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Ankara has also been uneasy over the developments in northern
Iraq, particularly those concerning the possible establishment of a
Kurdish state, which might eventually include the Kurdish-populated
southeast of Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
