<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Civil Servants Will Enjoy 13 Percent Salary Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Deputy Prime Minister
Lee Hsien Loong announced Thursday that his government has made a
major policy revision on public sector salaries and decided on 13
percent salary increases for civil servants in order to attract
and retain talent in civil service.
</P>
<P>
Making a ministerial statement at the Parliament, the deputy
prime minister said that the average total salary increase for a
civil servant from this revision is about 13 percent, including
the 3/4 month annual variable component (AVC), the 1/2 month
increase in performance bonus and the 5.8 percent increase in
monthly salaries.
</P>
<P>
Performance bonuses, which are currently paid only to civil
servants in the more senior grades, will become a big feature in
public sector, Lee said, stating that the government will pay a
performance bonus to all civil servants with an objective to
strengthen the link between pay and individual performance by
building up a performance-related component in the total wage
package of every civil servant.
</P>
<P>
He said this revision will significantly narrow the salary gaps
between the civil service and the private sector and make the
civil service able to retain sufficient talent to continue to
function stably and effectively.
</P>
<P>
Giving a detailed explanation to the policy revision, Lee said
that a full review conducted by the government has revealed that
salaries of most schemes of civil service have not been revised
for at least two years because of the economic downturn and
private sector's earnings have risen substantially with the strong
economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
The review also shows that the starting annual salaries of the
civil service are generally lagging significantly behind the 75th
percentile salaries in the private sector, he said
</P>
<P>
He underlined that resignation rates have also gone up across
the entire civil services, noting 284 officers from the Senior
Officer Service (or 12 percent of total staff strength) resigned
in the first five months of this year compared to 267 for the
whole of last year.
</P>
<P>
Excessive outflow will undermine the civil service and cause
public services to deteriorate, he stressed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
