<HEADLINE> New OIC Secretary General Named </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Former Moroccan Foreign
Minister Abdelouhed Belkziz has been named the new secretary-
general of the Organization of Islamic Conference (OIC).
</P>
<P>
He will succeed his fellow countryman Azeddine Laraki whose
four-year tenure as the 56-member grouping's secretary general
expires at the end of this year. Belkziz will assume the job on
January 1, 2001.
</P>
<P>
This was announced here Thursday by Malaysian Foreign Minister
Syed Hamid Albar, the current chairman of the ongoing 27th meeting
of the OIC foreign ministers.
</P>
<P>
Morocco, Bangladesh and Turkey were the three candidates vying
for the top OIC post.
</P>
<P>
Syed Hamid said Abdelouhed's selection was made possible with
the spirit of cooperation and Muslim brotherhood shown by
Bangladesh and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
To a question on whether the two countries had withdrawn their
candidacies, Syed Hamid said "the question of withdrawal did not
arise."
</P>
<P>
During consultations with representatives from the countries
involved, both agreed to support the Moroccan candidate, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We arrived at the decision supported by everybody based on
consensus," Syed Hamid said.
</P>
<P>
He said all agreed that there should not be any election for
the secretary-general's post to avoid the perception that Muslim
countries are divided.
</P>
<P>
The four-day meeting opened here Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
