<HEADLINE> Budget for Fiscal 2000-2001 Passed in Bangladesh Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Amid opposition boycott, Bangladeshi
parliament Thursday passed the national budget for fiscal 2000-
2001 amounting to 428.59 billion taka (8.24 billion U.S. dollars)
with overall deficit of 186.61 billion taka (3.59 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The opposition, except a few members of Jatiya Party, continued
their abstention when Finance Minister Shah A.M.S. Kibria moved
the money bill to pass the budget through voice vote by treasury
bench members.
</P>
<P>
Several hundred cut motions were submitted by opposition
members of parliament, but those motions were not moved because of
their absence. Speaker Humayun Rashid Chowdhury applied guillotine
to quicken the passage of the budget after brief discussions from
10 a.m.to 12 a.m..
</P>
<P>
Referring to the much-criticized huge deficit in the budget,
the finance minister said the deficit would be met by foreign
grants and loans, domestic resources and bank borrowings.
</P>
<P>
The national budget, placed in the parliament by the finance
minister on June 8, was severely battered by the opposition
parties for its enormous deficit.
</P>
<P>
To protest the unilateral passage of the national budget in the
parliament, the four-party opposition alliance has announced a new
program to call on countrywide hartal (destructive strike) on July
2.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
