country's economy. It would slash subsidies that have kept
utility rated outrageously low, devise a new energy policy and
wipe out unpaid wages, tax breaks and other obligations that have
sapped government spending power.
</P>
<P>
-- The U.S. Supreme Court, ruling 5 to 4 in a New Jersey case,
said the government cannot bar doctors from using a procedure
widely known as "partial-birth control," because it may be the
most medically appropriate way of terminating some pregnancies.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- The Fed left short-term interest rates unchanged but warned
that it would resume efforts to slow the economy if growth
rebounds this summer.
</P>
<P>
-- Sprint is not giving up on its merger with Worldcom, even
though a deal looks improbable in the wake of a U.S. Justice
Department suit aimed at blocking the transaction on antitrust
grounds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
