<DOCNO> XIE20000629.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Centuries-old Chinese Writing Tools Survive Country's Development ( 1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Zhou Meihong, director of the
Oldhukaiwen Inkstick Factory in east China's Anhui Province, surfs
the net almost every day to check out what's happening in the
global stationery industry.
</P>
<P>
He also e-mails his clients in more than 20 countries,
including Japan, the Republic of Korea, India, the United States,
and Britain.
</P>
<P>
Zhou's factory, which always smells of burning vegetable and
animal oil, turns out Huizhou inksticks, the premiere Chinese ink
made of soot, using the same techniques that craftsmen employed 2,
000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Inksticks, along with writing brushes, inkslabs and Xuan paper,
also known as rice paper, all invented in China, have been
referred to as the "four treasures of study" since the Song
Dynasty (960-1279).
</P>
<P>
They have made a remarkable contribution to the recording of
Chinese history, promoting culture and boosting social progress,
and have long been regarded as symbols of the 5,000-year-old
Chinese civilization.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists have confirmed that the designs on painted
pottery made in the Neolithic Age were drawn with writing brushes,
and that the inscriptions on bones and tortoise shells of the
Shang Dynasty (16th-11th century B.C.), the earliest Chinese
characters were carved from patterns made by writing brushes and
Chinese ink.
</P>
<P>
The late Professor Zong Baihua, a scholar at Beijing University,
once said that calligraphy created with the "four treasures of the
study" is the symbol of Chinese culture, while architecture and
sculpture symbolize Western culture.
</P>
<P>
French President Jacques Chirac called calligraphy "the art of
Chinese art."
</P>
<P>
As China develops, more people are leaving their nation's
writing heritage behind, switching instead to fountain pens,
computers and the Internet as more convenient communication tools.
</P>
<P>
Some people fear the "four treasures of study" may someday fade
away -- just as the quill pen did.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000629.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwan Investors Seek Business Opportunities in Guangdong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DONGGUAN, (Guangdong), June 29 (Xinhua) -- Some 2,000 Taiwan
investors gathered together here in Dongguan, a major electronic
equipment production base in Guangdong Province in south China, to
seek new business opportunities.
</P>
<P>
Among the 2,000 investors who are attending the two-day
Guangdong-Taiwan Exchange Meeting for Economy, Technology and
Trade, more than 1,000 people are on the first visit to this
mainland city to make investment inspections, said organizers for
the meeting, which will be close today.
</P>
<P>
Tang Shubei, executive vice-president of the mainland's
Association for Relations Across the Taiwan Straits (ARATS) and
also deputy head of the Taiwan Affairs Office of the State Council,
told participating Taiwan investors to seize the chances and to
make greater efforts in promoting cooperation and development of
relations across the Taiwan Straits.
</P>
<P>
"Taiwan investors are now facing three opportunities: the
development of China's western region; the adjustment of the
industrial structure of the mainland and China's accession into
the World Trade Organization this year," Tang explained, adding
that he hoped Taiwan investors could further expand economic and
trade cooperation with Guangdong and other areas of the mainland.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-two cities of Guangdong Province have sent their
business delegations which have brought along a long list of
projects in pursuit of investment and cooperation to the meeting.
Special introductory workshops were organized to brief Taiwan
investors about investment environment and policies in those
cities.
</P>
<P>
While holding informal discussions with some Taiwan investors,
both Li Changchun, a member of the Political Bureau of the Central
Committee of the Communist Party of China (CPC) and also Party
Secretary of Guangdong Province, and Governor Lu Ruihua pledged
that they would go all out to help Taiwan investors solve problems
and difficulties in business.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, Taiwan investors have become Guangdong's second
largest source of overseas investment after Hong Kong. They have
set up 11,700 enterprises in Guangdong Province, and have pumped 8.
1 billion U.S. dollars into Guangdong by investing in these
businesses.
</P>
<P>
The volume of trade between Guangdong and Taiwan amounted to 13.
95 billion U.S. dollars in 1999, accounting for 10 percent of
Guangdong's total foreign trade.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
