<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Centuries-old Chinese Writing Tools Survive Country's Development ( 2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
However, Zhou said that his factory, the largest of its kind in
the country, has more business now than it has in 200 years.
</P>
<P>
"These four tools are not only writing tools of today but also
a symbol of culture and art. They are especially indispensable
tools for calligraphy and traditional Chinese painting, and with
the increasing worldwide interest in these artistic forms, there's
a bigger demand for them," said Guo Haitang, president of the
Association for Producers of Writing Brush and Paper, Ink Stick
and Slab.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that in China alone, at least 20 million people
practice calligraphy and traditional Chinese painting. An
increasing number of universities have offered calligraphy courses,
including some for doctorate degrees.
</P>
<P>
Bae Gyu Ha, from the Republic of Korea, is now studying for a
Ph.D. in calligraphy at Capital Normal University in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Influenced by an uncle who is a Sinologist, Bae became adept at
using writing brushes as a child.
</P>
<P>
"Calligraphy is a visible symbol of Chinese culture, so I've
made the study of calligraphy my career," said the 39-year-old Bae,
who has already published two books on calligraphy in his country.
</P>
<P>
Bae added that Chinese culture would not have as deeply
influenced Japan, the Republic of Korea, and many southeast Asia's
countries if there had been no writing brushes, Chinese ink, Xuan
paper and inkslabs.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, China has developed more than 1,000 new
products with high artistic value, such as inksticks and huge
inkslabs engraved with pictures of scenic spots and characters
recording major social events.
</P>
<P>
Liulichang Street in downtown Beijing, known as a "window to
Chinese culture" and flanked with more than 100 art shops selling
various writing brushes, inksticks and inkslabs, has now become a
major attraction in Beijing for domestic and overseas tourists and
art collectors.  
</P>
