<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Gets Two WB Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank (WB) approved on
Tuesday two loans to China totaling 360 million U.S. dollars,
according to sources from WB's China Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The loans will be used for two projects, namely the Yangtze
Dike Strengthening Project (210 million U.S. dollars) and the
Hebei Water and Environment Project (150 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The first project, with a total investment of 545 million U.S.
dollars, aims to help protect the river bank of the flood-prone
Yangtze River against erosion and improve critical sections of
existing main dikes by strengthening the river bank and flood
protection dikes.
</P>
<P>
Daniel Gunaratnam, project task manager of WB, said that this
project will help China improve its systems of flood protection
and response, dike management and operation along the Yangtze, "in
order to help mitigate terrible social and economic costs."
</P>
<P>
He predicted that the work will benefit an area of 21,000
square kilometers, and improve the quality of life for over 15
million people.
</P>
<P>
The Hebei Water and Environment Project, with a total
investment of 293 million U.S. dollars, is expected to create an
environmental setting capable of sustaining the long-term economic
growth of urban areas in this north China Province.
</P>
<P>
The project will do this by supporting the province in
implementing a long-term urban environmental service improvement
program that will help Hebei recover from past degradation of
water and land resources and provide an adequate supply of safe
water to its population and economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
