<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- The Lebanese Finance Ministry said in a statement that
the government income in the first five months of 2000 was 1,829.7
billion liras (1.2 billion U.S. dollars) against a spending of 3,
794.7 billion liras (2.5 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iranian President Mohammad Khatami stressed here on
Tuesday more attention should be paid to industry as it serves as
the "foundation and stronghold of human society."
</P>
<P>
Addressing a seminar on the role of industries in national
development, the president also underlined the importance of
guaranteeing investment in manufacturing and industrial sectors.
</P>
<P>
Grounds should be prepared for attracting and guaranteeing
security of investment by both Iranians and foreigners, Khatami
said. He also highlighted research and standardization of
industries in the modern competitive world and liberalization of
banking facilities for investment.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian Finance Minister Mohamed Medhat Hassaneen said
the cash liquidity shortage is on the way to an end as the
government is able to repay dues to companies.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's Al-Ahram newspaper quoted the minister as saying the
volume of overdue arrears has hit 12.6 billion Egyptian pounds (3.
65 billion U.S. dollars). With the 1999/2000 fiscal year (started
on July 1, 1999) to end on June 30, the government will have paid
off 8.6 billion pounds (2.49 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
He dismissed as baseless reports that the government's return to
borrowing from abroad was due to the replacement of foreign debts
with domestic debts, reiterating that they are not related to each
other. To achieve a growth rate of 6.5 percent, local and
international savings should be used, together with an increase in
investments at a rate of 24 percent of the gross domestic product
(GDP), he added.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's domestic debts now hit 146.2 billion pounds (42.38
billion dollars), accounting for 50 percent of the GDP, while
foreign debts reaching 28.2 billion dollars. And foreign debt
service stands at 1.5 billion pounds (434.7 million dollars) per
year, he added.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanon's foreign trade deficit hit 2.152 billion U.S.
dollars in the first five months of this year, down by 7.56 percent
from 2.328 billion dollars during the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics by the Lebanese Customs Electronic
Center, the volume of imports totalled 2.448 billion dollars during
the five-month period, down by 4.38 percent from 2.56 billion
dollars during the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, exports volume stood at 296 million dollars, up by
21.62 percent from 232 million dollars of last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
