<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Journalists Freed After Being Detained by Fiji's Coup Leader EDS-Updates with Speight's Comments, Military Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Nine journalists were released on
Thursday after being held by Fiji's coup leader George Speight in
the country's parliamentary compound, the Australian Broadcasting
Corporation (ABC) TV reported.
</P>
<P>
The ABC quoted Speight as saying the nine journalists, who were
reported to have been taken hostage, have now safely left the area.
</P>
<P>
After about an hour in parliamentary compound, the journalists
were escorted out the front gate by several Speight's gunmen.
</P>
<P>
The reporters, mostly from international media, had attended a
regular nightly press conference where Speight attacked military
plans to cordon off the suburbs around the parliament.
</P>
<P>
Speight said that at the end of the conference he told the
journalists if they wanted to leave, they could - but he did not
recommend it.
</P>
<P>
He said his guards had been advised not to let anybody in or
out, as they had received threats from outside the complex.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the ABC quoted the journalists as saying that when
they tried to leave, the rebels told them they could not guarantee
their safety once they walked through the gate and they could be
shot if they approached a military checkpoint.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Fiji's military law authorities confirmed plans to
set up a military zone surrounding the compound where Speight has
been holding hostages since May 19, the ABC said.
</P>
<P>
Military officers were expected to announce an order Friday for
the evacuation of residents in an area up to two kilometers around
parliament.
</P>
<P>
Only Red Cross staff would be allowed through to take daily
supplies and food to the hostages.
</P>
<P>
The move was said to be part of a military plan to isolate the
coup group, the ABC said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
