<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks End Stronger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 29 (Xinhua) - The Australian stockmarket closed
higher Thursday after the U.S. Federal Bank decided not to raise
official interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark S&AMP;P/ASX200 index was 40.6 points higher at 3,254.
5, while the all ordinaries index was 39.9 points higher at 3,205.
5.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 1.148 billion shares worth 2.224 billion
Australian dollars (133.66 billion U.S. dollars). There were 118
rising stocks, 717 falling ones and 652 steady.
</P>
<P>
The market was led by News Corp., which finished one dollar
higher at 22.30 Australian dollars. National Australia Bank was up
30.5 cents to 27.431 Australian dollars, ANZ was 25 cents stronger
to 12.74 Australian dollars, while Publishing &AMP; Broadcasting was
steady at 12.80 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
But the Commonwealth was 20 cents lower to 27.30 Australian
dollars and Westpac was 15 cents lower to 11.90 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
In the telecommunications sector, Cable &AMP; Wireless Optus rose
15.7 cents to 4.984 Australian dollars, while Telstra's ordinary
shares rose 8.6 cents to 6.764 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
In the resources sector, Anglo-British miner Rio Tinto added 36.
9 cents to 26.499 Australian dollars while BHP dropped 34.2 cents
to 19.308 Australian dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
