<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Social Safety Net Urged for Thailand to Protect Poor Farmers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Thailand needs a new social safety
net since the rural poor were proven the hardest hit in the
economic crisis and the agriculture sector's ability to reabsorb
low-skilled urban labor during recession turned out to be limited,
a report on the impact of the 1997 crisis on Thailand's rural
sector said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The study, conducted by the Mekong Environment and Resource
Institute in collaboration with the World Bank and the agriculture
and cooperatives ministry of Thailand, surveyed more than 1,600
households in the north, northeast and central regions of Thailand
during the 1995-1996 and 1998-1999 crop years.
</P>
<P>
The study found that the poor have borne the brunt of the
crisis, with their expenditures and income falling both in real
terms and when comparing to those of the rich.
</P>
<P>
Opposite to hypothesis that urban unemployment resulted in a
large emigration back to the rural areas and in a sharp decrease
in remittances, the study found that there is actually little
signs of a massive urban to rural migration, although a slowdown
in rural emigration does exist.
</P>
<P>
Although net remittances declined for all but the richest
households, the study found that the poor are less reliant on
remittances than the rich. However, overall off-farm income,
including remittances, declined for the poor, but not for the rich.
</P>
<P>
The central region performed much better in terms of
consumption and income compared to both the north and northeast,
with the north particularly hard-hit.
</P>
<P>
These findings are consistent with the fact that the poor
derive most of their income from the labor market rather than from
farming, whereas the situation is reverse for the richer farmers.
</P>
<P>
The study also found that there is no evidence of a credit
crunch during the crisis as expected, and neither large decline in
outstanding loans is found in the data.
</P>
<P>
The report indicates that poverty alleviation measures that
focus on price supports and credit subsidies will only have a
limited impact on the rural poor because they derive only small
share of their income from crop cultivation.
</P>
<P>
It urges the Thai government to establish temporary social
programs to alleviate the effect of recessions on the rural poor.
</P>
<P>
In the medium and long term, measures to increase access to off-
farm employment, such as by developing rural infrastructure and
increasing the flexibility of the rural labor force, should be
adopted to improve the well-being of the rural poor, the report
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
