<HEADLINE> Nigerian Power Company Black out Governor's Office for Bills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Total black-out descended on to the
governor' s office Wednesday in the southern Nigerian state of
Osun when the country' s National Electric Power Authority (NEPA)
made real its promise to entertain no "sacred cow" in collecting
overdue electricity bills.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian press Thursday quoted NEPA officials as saying that
Osun state government owed a 36 million naira (360,000 U.S.
dollars) electricity debt to the state-owned power company.
</P>
<P>
Affected in the mass disconnection are the Governor's Office,
government agencies, the state secretariat and House of Assembly
complex.
</P>
<P>
An official of NEPA disclosed that the power cut exercise was
resorted to after Governor Adebisi Adebayo repeatedly reneged on
several promises to pay the three million naira (30,000 U.S.
dollars) monthly bill since the inauguration of his administration
over a year ago. Black-outs are commonplace for average
citizens in Nigeria, the most populous African nation, which makes
the NEPA an easy target for severe criticism from the public.
</P>
<P>
But the NEPA recently refuted that the delay or non-payment of
the electricity bills sometime leave it in a plight of having no
money for the maintenance, thus causing collapse of the national
power grid from time to time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
