<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Double-digit Economic Growth Expected in HK This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Standard Chartered Bank has
revised the real GDP growth forecast of Hong Kong in 2000 to 10
percent, from its previous prediction of eight percent made in
March this year.
</P>
<P>
Economic figures released in recent months showed that trade
continues to perform very well in Hong Kong. Retained imports are
growing strongly in recent months, signifying that domestic demand
is set to remain firm in the coming months, according a press
release of Standard Chartered Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The economic upswing in China's mainland is having an
increasingly positive impact on Hong Kong, particularly through
trade, stock market activities and tourism, the press released
said.
</P>
<P>
"Worries of rapid increases in interest rates and a 'hard
landing' in the United States have subsided," said K.C. Kwok,
regional chief economist of Standard Chartered.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Federal Reserve has decided to keep interest rates on
hold Wednesday. The market consensus is expecting an increase of a
further 25 basis points in interest rates in the second half of
this year, rather than 75 basis points or more as predicted a
month ago.
</P>
<P>
"The 10 percent growth forecast for the year 2000 as a whole is
a relatively conservative one," said Kwok. "The market is always
worried about the downside risk. But increasingly, the surprise is
likely to come on the upside." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
