<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Leading Metropolis Has 235 Centenarians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 29 (Xinhua) -- She witnessed the fall of China's
last feudal dynasty in 1911 and the start of the People's Republic
in 1949. She experienced numerous wars and disasters. She has seen
her hometown of Shanghai revel in prosperity in the 1920s, only to
decline in later years, and now re-emerge as a gleaming metropolis
in east Asia.
</P>
<P>
Sun Duanqing, who at 109 is the oldest citizen in this city of
13 million in east China, has become a symbol of longevity.
</P>
<P>
Sun, born in 1891, was recently determined to be the oldest of
Shanghai's 235 centenarians. That total is nearly three times the
1990 figure, according to a report in today's Wenhui Daily.
</P>
<P>
Female centenarians outnumbered the males 199 to 36. The 103-
year-old Zhang Zongying and 102-year-old Huang Ouxin are the only
married couple in the lot.
</P>
<P>
"The extension of human life can reflect economic, scientific
and medical development of one country, and is a token of the
improvement of senior citizens' living quality," the newspaper
quoted an unnamed expert on population aging as saying.
</P>
<P>
The number of centenarians in Shanghai soared from only one in
1953 to 208 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The leading industrial and commercial city also took the lead
in China to become a graying society at the end of the 1970s; the
life expectancy of local residents is now 75.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that there were 284,900 people age 80 or above
in Shanghai by the end of last year, making up 12 percent of its
population of people 60 and above.
</P>
<P>
Sociologists have urged the government and society to pay more
attention to the daily care and health promotion of the elderly,
said the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The elderly, especially those living alone, should enjoy better
and free services such as house keeping, medical care and
financial assistance, said Zhu Jiming, deputy director of the
Shanghai Research Center of Geriatrics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000629.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Start Gene Sequencing of Pigs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 29 (Xinhua) -- China will start a gene sequencing
project to upgrade breeds of pigs and promote studies on xeno-
transplantation and biological drugs, said a Chinese scientist in
Beijing today.
</P>
<P>
This is a follow-up to Chinese scientists' successful
completion of one percent of the sequencing of the human genome,
said Zhang Meng, a spokesman of the Human Genome Research Center
of the Genetics Institute, the Chinese Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said that though Germany, Denmark and other European
countries have already started similar joint research projects,
Chinese scientists see greater potential in their own undertaking.
</P>
<P>
Pork is the major source of animal protein in the Chinese diet,
and China has the largest pork output in the world. Scientists
hope that with a working draft of the pig genome map, they will be
able to upgrade the breed of pigs and promote the pig raising
industry.
</P>
<P>
The project is also the second project of the China biological
resources genome program. The first was the China hybrid super
paddle genome project, which was launched last month.
</P>
<P>
The pig gene sequencing project has drawn interest from Danish
scientists, entrepreneurs and government officials, who have
suggested that they cooperate with Chinese scientists in the work.
</P>
<P>
Genetic technology is regarded as one of the most important
advanced scientific technologies in the world. Many scientists
believe that the technology will have an even deeper impact on
humankind than information technology. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
