<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WTO Must Adapt to Global Trade Trend: Supachai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 29 (Xinhua) -- As the global trade trend is
changing due to advanced information technology, the World Trade
Organization WTO) must adapt itself to the new environment,
Supachai Panitchpakdi, the WTO Director-General-in-waiting and
Deputy Prime Minister of Thailand, said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The World Trade Organization must change its rules and
functions in order to be relevant and effective, " he said, when
delivering a keynote speech at the opening ceremony of the Third
World Marketing Conference, which is being held here on June 29 to
30.
</P>
<P>
"Because of the rapid development of the information and
communication," he said, "goods, services, investment, and
information are now being traded in a much cheaper and faster
manner."
</P>
<P>
More business activities, such as marketing, sales and delivery
of goods and services, and payments, will be conducted
electronically with the revolution in e-commerce and internet, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
"So far on the global scale, the WTO has already done
prominently well to promote e-commerce trend with certain
agreements such as the Information Technology Agreement signed in
1996, " he remarked.
</P>
<P>
Despite those positive aspects of the WTO, he said, certain
improvements are necessary.
</P>
<P>
The fact that more than 30 nations are awaiting their WTO
accession is a "true testimony" for the importance of the
organization, he said.
</P>
<P>
Among those nations, Supachai pointed out, China's accession to
the WTO is attracting the most media attention, and will have a
great impact to the world trade system.
</P>
<P>
"Over the last 14 years, China has showed its strong
determination to become a WTO member," he noted, "and has made
many significant concessions on tariff reduction."
</P>
<P>
"This shows that it is very important for the WTO to include
all the nations, and China's membership will have a great global
impact, politically and economically," he stated.
</P>
<P>
China's accession to the organization will help set up a new
balance in the multilateral world trade system, and will also
offer many new trade opportunities for other countries with its
huge domestic market, he said.
</P>
<P>
At present, the top priority for the WTO is to strengthen
confidence among its 136 members, especially those developing
countries, Supachai said.
</P>
<P>
"The WTO will certainly continue to assume the leading role in
promoting trade liberalization while providing the necessary rules
and disciplines for global stability, transparency, and security
in today's complex international place," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
