<HEADLINE> Roundup: Albright Ends Shuttles, Three-Way Summit Delayed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 29 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright wound up her shuttles between Israel and Palestine
Wendesday night, failing to clear doubt over a much-anticipated
Washington summit between Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak,
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Albright, who returned to the region Tuesday evening, held a
first meeting with Barak, in which Barak briefed her about his
positions on all key issues in the final-status talks and the two
assessed the possibility of holding the summit.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Albright first held talks with Israeli Foreign
Minister David Levy, then travelled to the West Bank city of
Ramallah for a two-hour session with Arafat. In the afternoon, she
returned to Jerusalem for another meeting with Barak, who had been
pushing hard for the summit that he believes could conceivably
culminate in a settlement of Israel's half-century conflict with
the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Although all parties concerned refrained from saying outright
that Albright's current shuttles failed to produce positive
results, they indicated that her mission ended with delay of
holding the summit at least.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian side had rejected Barak's suggestion that the
summit be held in early July, asking instead that another round of
talks be held in the U.S. next week between negotiators from the
two sides before they are ready to decide whether to hold the
summit.
</P>
<P>
Senior Palestinian officials said Arafat is unwilling to go to a
summit without a prior assurance as to the outcome, and Arafat is
demanding first to know how far Barak is willing to compromise on
matters of borders, Jerusalem, refugees and other key issues needed
to be settled in the final-status talks.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Arafat also demands that the leftover interim issues,
such as the release of more Palestinians from Israeli jails and the
third West Bank redeployment, be implemented before the summit.
</P>
<P>
Arafat reportedly complained during his talks with Albright that
Israel is willing to give back all the territories demanded by
Egypt, Lebanon and Syria, but is unwilling when it comes to the
Palestinians' demand.
</P>
<P>
Barak gave a different explanation about the summit, saying "the
talks between negotiating teams at this point amount to nothing,
and that the only way forward is for him to sit down with Arafat
and Clinton and make the difficult decisions needed for a deal."
</P>
<P>
He also stressed "the process will go forward if, and only if,
there is a summit."
</P>
<P>
Officials at the Prime Minister's Office sided with Barak,
saying there is "no chance" of satisfying the Palestinians'
expectations regarding the interim issues at this point, and that
Barak does not intend to set out his positions until he is at the
summit.
</P>
<P>
At a joint press conference with Barak at the conclusion of
their meeting Wednesday afternoon, Albright noted both sides are
continuing serious negotiations on the permanent status agreement
and understand the historical opportunity at hand to reach an
agreement, cautioning both sides against trying to get 100 percent
of their demands met.
</P>
<P>
She also promised to report her findings about the possibility
of holding the summit to Clinton, who will decide when it is
appropriate to hold the summit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000629.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Moves to Address Mass Housing Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government said
Thursday that it has adopted a market specialization approach that
would match fund sources with potential house owners.
</P>
<P>
In a press statement issued here, President Joseph Estrada said
he expects the system to benefit overseas Filipino workers, trade
union members and private sector employees.
</P>
<P>
"Under this initiative, the Social Security System will serve
workers in the private sector while the Government Service
Insurance System will handle the requirement of government
employees and teachers," Estrada said.
</P>
<P>
He added the Home Development Mutual Fund will serve the needs
of the Philippine National Police and the Armed Forces of the
Philippine.
</P>
<P>
Aside from this, the president said, the government is seeking
to establish a secondary mortgage market to ensure sustainability
of housing funds.
</P>
<P>
Under this initiative, he added, housing agencies would develop
the secondary housing market, with the help of private
institutional investors.
</P>
<P>
In turn, Estrada noted, this would develop the sustainable
liquidity of the socialized housing sector.
</P>
<P>
Mass housing remains one of the president's centerpiece
programs,alongside food security, peace and order, the right
against graft and corruption, and electoral reforms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
