<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economic Reform Target "Attainable": Turkish Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Recep Onal, Turkish state minister
for economy, has said it is unnecessary to revise targets of a
three-year economic stability program, adding the program
objectives remain "attainable."
</P>
<P>
The minister made the remarks after Turkish State Planning
Organization (DPT) reported Wednesday that in the first quarter,
the drop in inflation was below program objectives, the current
account deficit and foreign trade deficit were higher than
predicted, Turkish Daily News reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has implemented its economic program, supported by a
four-billion-U.S. dollar stand-by deal signed last December with
the International Monetary Fund (IMF), without any concessions so
far.
</P>
<P>
Under the program, Turkey pledged to reduce its chronic
inflation and budget deficits, undertake a comprehensive
privatization program and carry out reforms in the agricultural
sector within three years.
</P>
<P>
The government aims to reduce inflation to 20 percent in 2000,
10 percent in 2001 and 5.0 percent in 2002.
</P>
<P>
Onal just concluded his talks with the Organization for Economic
Cooperation and Development (OECD)'s Council of Ministers in Paris.
</P>
<P>
He said "OECD members believe that Turkey's stability program is
very coherent and its chronic economic problems could be overcome
only through this program."
</P>
<P>
The minister indicated all OECD members have completed their
privatization of state-run enterprises and for that reason Turkey
should be accelerating its privatization precess.
</P>
<P>
Although DPT's less promising briefing, the Central Bank said on
Wednesday the disinflation program is "firmly" on track.
</P>
<P>
It said Turkey has met the end-1999 performance criteria on both
fiscal and monetary fronts as part of the three-year stand-by deal,
so the confidence in the business sector has improved.
</P>
<P>
Early this month, the head of IMF's Turkey desk, Carlos
Cottarelli, also said Turkey's chronic inflation will drop
significantly by the end of the year if Ankara sticks to the tight
IMF-backed program that has already begun to bear fruit.
</P>
<P>
"If the current trend continues, Turkey will very much be near
to the targeted inflation level," determined as 20-25 percent, he
said during his review of the program in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
"But this, of course, depends on the continuation of the current
policies," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000629.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interpellation not to Topple President: Indonesian Speaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Speaker of the Indonesia's House
of Representatives (DPR) Akbar Tandjung said here Thursday that a
motion for interpellation which has just passed by the House is
not intended to topple President Abdurrahman Wahid.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after the passage of the motion, Tandjung
made it clear that, "This motion for interpellation is not
intended to unseat President Abdurrahman Wahid. Not at all. This
is just intended to give political education."
</P>
<P>
He also said that the motion "will not be intended to clear the
way for the People's Consultatives Assembly's (MPR) special
session in August."
</P>
<P>
"This motion also will not endanger the position of Abdurrahman
Wahid as a president. But may be this will be a kind of progress
report from the House. We will submit this to the MPR as an input,
" he said.
</P>
<P>
"We have to safeguard the leadership of President Wahid, but we
have to give him a critical opinion over his policies including in
the case of the dismissal of cabinet minister," he added.
</P>
<P>
The House passed a motion for interpellation of President Wahid
on Thursday. Of the 431 existing votes, the motion gained 332
votes, rejected by 63 while 36 votes abstains.
</P>
<P>
The motion which was sponsored by the Indonesian Democratic
Party of Struggle (PDI Perjuangan) and the Golkar party is aimed
at summoning and seeking explanation from the president over the
dismissal of his two cabinet ministers namely Laksamana Sukardi (
from the PDI perjuangan) and Yusuf Kalla (Golkar Party).
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the President said that the dismissal of the two
ministers on April 25 was made due to the alleged involvement of
Sukardi and Kalla in corruption practices. But however, the two
rejected such an allegation.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Syamsul Ma'arif of the Golkar Party said that the
House will conduct an internal meeting to set a schedule to summon
the president.
</P>
<P>
"We will hold a meeting on July 3. And it is expected that the
president will be able to meet our summon before July 21," he said.
</P>
<P>
"If we finds evidences confirming the involvement of Sukardi
and Kalla in corruption cases, they should be tried. But if not,
and the president can not also give any evidences confirming
corruption practices of Sukardi and Kalla, then the president
should rehabilitate their names," Ma'arif added.
</P>
<P>
It seems that the motion will be the first time for the country
's political history where the president was summoned by the House
through a motion for interpellation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
