<HEADLINE> Fiji Military Authorities Squeeze Coup Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
According to the Australian radio ABC, the army spokesman
Filipo Tarakinikini said Thursday that if the hostages' lives are
endangered, the offer of amnesty to the hostage-takers will be
reviewed.
</P>
<P>
The coup leader George Speight ignored Wednesday the military's
ultimatum to sign an accord, according to which the future
president of the country should de decided by the Great Council of
Chiefs. the council has previously thrown its support behind the
stepped down president Ratu Mara. While George Speight wants to
install the former vice-president Josefo Iloilo as president.
</P>
<P>
The military authorities announced Wednesday that they will
establish an interim government within a week, casting aside
Speight and his supporters.
</P>
<P>
The military has canvassed the possibility of blockading the
parliament compound in a bid to isolate the coup group but ruled
out using force to free the 27 hostages. 
</P>
