<HEADLINE> Tanzania Telecom Finds Foreign Partner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzanian government has
 identified a consortium of German and Dutch firms as the
preferred strategic partner for the privatization of Tanzania
Telecommunications Company Limited (TTCL), the largest phone
company in the eastern African country, local newspapers reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzanian Presidential Parastatal Sector Reform Commission
(PSRC) announced Wednesday that the consortium comprised of
Detecon of Germany and MSI of the Netherlands has offered 120
million U.S. dollars for a 35 percent stake in TTCL.
</P>
<P>
It is also committed to increasing the number of telephone
lines to 800, 000 from the present 140,000 by December 2003.
</P>
<P>
"The Government of Tanzania is happy to accept this offer and
congratulates the Detecon/MSI consortium on its successful bid,"
the PRSC Executive Chairman John Rubambe was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The two companies have experience, excellent skills and
adequate resources, which, through its control of the TTCL board
and management, will enable the company to strengthen its
financial performance and customer services, the chairman said.
</P>
