<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya to Enact Ethics Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan lawmakers and cabinet
ministers will be required to declare their wealth if a bill on
the Public Service Code of Conduct and Ethics becomes law, the
Daily Nation newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The bill, which bans civil servants from receiving gifts or
money to influence their work, is expected to be tabled in
parliament in a fortnight.
</P>
<P>
The bill is aimed at curbing widespread corruption,
inefficiency and misconduct in the civil service, said the
newspapers.
</P>
<P>
The bill, coming in the wake of pressure from the International
Monetary Fund and the World Bank, defines misconduct as
corruption, misuse of public office and sexual harassment.
</P>
<P>
A wide range of civil servants are covered in the bill which
aims to enhance public confidence in their integrity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
