<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Israeli newspapers on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright returned to
Washington Thursday after finding that Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat are not yet ready to
hold a summit.
</P>
<P>
Although all the main players involved refrained from saying
outright that the summit will not take place, Palestinian officials
said they have rejected a suggestion that it be held on July 15,
proposing instead that another round of talks be held in the U.S.
next week between the negotiating teams.
</P>
<P>
For fear of being pressured by U.S. President Bill Clinton and
Barak on matters of territory, refugees and Jerusalem, Arafat is
demanding first to know how far the Israeli government is willing
to compromise.
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak has asked Knesset
(Parliament) member Dan Meridor from the Center Party to join his
government as a minister without portfolio and take responsibility
for the Mossad, the Shin Bet security service and the Atomic Energy
Commission, which until now have been under the direct
responsibility of the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Meridor, who is currently the chairman of the
Knesset Foreign Affairs and Defense Committee and is a former
justice minister and finance minister, will take part in the
meetings of the security cabinet and in ministerial panels that
will deal with the negotiations with the Palestinians and perhaps
with the Syrians.
</P>
<P>
Meridor has already turned down an earlier proposal by Barak,
according to which he would have become tourism minister in place
of Amnon Lipkin-Shahak, who was this week appointed transport
minister in place of Yitzhak Mordechai who resigned after being
indicted on sexual assault charges against him.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak said Wednesday that "within
36 hours" he will announce a way to bring about an end to the
doctors' strike, which goes into its 113th day on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Barak intends to bring the wage and working conditions issues to
arbitration, which was recommended by the non-binding mediators who
have been hearing from both Health Minister Shlomo Benizri and the
Israel Medical Association for a month.
</P>
<P>
President Ezer Weizman, on a visit to Ashkelon, a port city in
the south, Wednesday called on the government to bring a quick end
to the strike, saying it was "pathetic" to see empty hospitals and
that the sanctions endangered lives.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak Wednesday decided not to
take any action at present to stop the construction work at the
Temple Mount by the Moselm Wakf (or Islamic religious trust).
</P>
<P>
Barak held an urgent meeting to discuss the security situation
on the Temple Mount in light of the protests over the construction.
</P>
<P>
He also instructed the authorities to allow archaeologists from
the Antiquities Authority to the site and to prevent the
construction work from developing into more extensive construction
activity. 
</P>
