<HEADLINE> Kenya Seeks Power Plant Suppliers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has appealed
to bidders to supply emergency thermal power plants to help reduce
the dwindling power supply, local newspapers reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The government has applied for credit from the International
Development Association to finance the supply.
</P>
<P>
Available documents indicate that the government is asking for
a 75- megawatt plant and a 30-megawatt plant to be installed in
the capital Nairobi on a short-term basis for six to 12 months.
</P>
<P>
The plants are required to be operational by August and until
April next year when the long rains are expected.
</P>
<P>
The prospective suppliers are to submit their bids to the
Energy Ministry by July 10 and the plants are expected to be
operational within six to 10 weeks from the award of contracts.
</P>
<P>
Kenya has experienced a long-spell drought, resulting in low
water levels of reservoirs which affects the power generation.
Currently the country is facing a shortage of 100 mega watts.
</P>
