<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: New Change on Zimbabwe's Political Arena </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
by Zhu Shixiang
</P>
<P>
HARARE, June 29 (Xinhua) -- A big change has taken place in the
Zimbabwean political arena with a new opposition party posing a
threat to the 20-year-domination of the ruling party.
</P>
<P>
In the fifth parliamentary election on June 24-25, the ruling
Zimbabwe African National Union-Patriotic Front (Zanu-pf) won
narrowly with 62 seats against 57 seats for the Movement for
Democratic Change, which was formed nine months ago. It was the
first time the ruling party lost many seats to a opposition party.
</P>
<P>
From the country's independence in 1980, Zanu-pf, which fought
a bitter war against British colonialists, had enjoyed support
from the majority of people due to its efforts in improving its
peoples' lives by building schools and hospitals, providing free
primary education and creating new jobs.
</P>
<P>
In the just-ended election, Zanu-pf still had massive backing
from people in the rural areas, but lost heavily in towns because
of the difficult economic situation greatly affecting urban
residents.
</P>
<P>
But, when the International Monetary Fund and the World Bank
demanded Zimbabwe to introduce economic structural adjustment
program in the early 1990s, the hard economic times were triggered
off. Unemployment soared. Interest rates shot up. Foreign
investment flowed out of the country. The prices of basic
commodities, such as bread and cooking oil, rose dramatically.
</P>
<P>
Many people, especially those in towns, began to complain that
Zanu-pf had forgotten them.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwe Congress of Trade Unions (ZCTU) took advantage of
the situation and launched the new party, the Movement for
Democratic Change, which turned out to be "a black horse" in the
parliamentary election.
</P>
<P>
With the backing of the working class, MDC challenged the once
unchallenged Zanu-pf and reaped its first victory when it
mobilized supporters to vote against the proposed constitutional
reform draft during the referendum in February this year.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the MDC has surged ahead with bold confidence.
</P>
<P>
When President Robert Mugabe announced that the election would
be held in June this year, MDC made it clear that it would field
candidates for all the 120 contested seats. The MDC did give
Zanu-pf a hard time during the parliamentary election.
</P>
<P>
However, Zanu-pf is still in control of the parliament since
President Mugabe is empowered by the constitution to appoint 30
people to Parliament. This allows Mugabe to form a government
merely from his Zanu-pf.
</P>
<P>
But political observers have urged him to form a coalition
government which he did with Zimbabwe African People Union (Zapu)
at independence in 1980.
</P>
<P>
After the marginal victory in the parliamentary election, the
government is faced with the big job of reversing the slowdown of
the economy.
</P>
<P>
But the pressing issue that the Zanu-pf should tackle is land
distribution. Only 4,500 whites own 70 percent of fertile land
while more than 12 million people are still living on very poor
soils in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Just before the election, the freedom fighters, who fought for
independence, occupied about 1,500 farms owned by whites, saying
Zanu-pf was taking too long in getting back the land from British
settlers.
</P>
<P>
These veterans have vowed to remain on the occupied farms until
the government buys enough farms to settle them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000629.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IBM Builds World's Most Powerful Computer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 28 (Xinhua) -- International Business
Machines Corp. (IBM) announced Wednesday it has built the most
powerful supercomputer in the world.
</P>
<P>
According to IBM's news release, the new computer can perform
12.3 trillion operations per second, three times faster than the
next-fastest computer.
</P>
<P>
The system was made for the Department of Energy's Accelerated
Strategic Computing Initiative (ASCI) and could ease congressional
opposition to the United States' signing the Comprehensive Test
Ban Treaty, banning all actual nuclear weapons testing worldwide.
</P>
<P>
"Without underground testing, we need simulations to make sure
the stockpile is safe, reliable and operational," said David
Cooper, a member of the President's Council on Computing and chief
information officer of Lawrence Livermore Labs in California,
where the system will be run.
</P>
<P>
Called ASCI White, it will churn factors involved in a nuclear
detonation, including the weapon's age and design. This could
eventually allow U.S. government to manage its entire stockpile of
nuclear weapons without any real nuclear tests, Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government, which paid 110 million U.S. dollars for
the system, sought development of such a computer in the early
1990s in anticipation of a ban on underground nuclear testing,
which President Bill Clinton imposed this year, according to a
report by CNN.
</P>
<P>
Previous versions in the ASCI program have included the red
series by Intel, and the blue series by SGI/Cray and IBM. Although
each was the most powerful of its time, the new White version for
the first time allows scientists to factor in a host of variables
when running a simulation, CNN said.
</P>
<P>
The ASCI White is also powerful enough to process an Internet
commerce transaction for every person on Earth in less than one
minute, industry analysts believe.
</P>
<P>
That's three times more powerful than the previous champ, IBM's
ASCI Blue Pacific, and 1,000 times more powerful than "Deep Blue,"
the computer which defeated world chess champion Gary Kasparov in
1997, they added.
</P>
<P>
The complexity of the new system will boost IBM's marketing
efforts more than the computer will impact the earnings and
revenue for the company which is already the leading supplier of
supercomputing systems with 30 percent of the global market share
in 1999, said Debra Goldfarb, an analyst with technology research
firm International Data Corp.
</P>
<P>
Smaller versions of this computer are already used in weather
forecasting and tracking credit card fraud, said David Turek,
IBM's vice president for deep computing. A smaller version of the
ASCI computer also helped scientists map the human genome, said
David Nowak, deputy associate director of Livermore Labs.
</P>
<P>
IBM officials and analysts said parts of the design of ASCI
White, which connects 512 separate computers together with high
performance switches and software, could be built into computers
used for everything from electronic business to designing cars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000629.0210 </DOCNO>
