<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beet Webworms Hit N. China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Insects are devastating farms
in north China's Hebei Province, threatening the growth of
agricultural crops, grassland and forests.
</P>
<P>
Officials at the Provincial Agricultural Department said that
beet webworms have devastated Zhangjiakou, Chengde, Qinhuangdao,
Tangshan and other areas in Hebei since May.
</P>
<P>
The insects pose serious threats to the growth of maize, potato
and vegetables, officials said.
</P>
<P>
The beet webworms have damaged 8.5 million mu (about 567,000
hectares) of farmland, grassland and forests, including 2.5
million mu which was seriously affected. Some farmland will have
no yields this year.
</P>
<P>
Since May, it has rained several times in Zhangjiakou and
Chengde. The rains and moderate temperature have provided an ideal
breeding ground for insects.
</P>
<P>
In seriously affected areas, a square meter of land has as many
as 1,000 beet webworms.
</P>
<P>
In Wanquan and Huaian counties, beet webworms, locusts and
cabbage moths destroyed grassland and farmland, turning thousands
of hectares of maize and potato into barren fields.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government has galvanized people and allocated
money to fight beet webworms, and is doing all it can to prevent
the further spread of the insects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
