<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000629.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Improves Crops Mix </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Dropping prices and drought will
reduce wheat planting areas by nearly one quarter in China during
the spring season.
</P>
<P>
According to figures released by the National Bureau of
Statistics NBS) today planting areas of spring wheat dropped by
780,000 hectares, or 23.6 percent from last year to 2.55 million
hectares.
</P>
<P>
Planting areas of spring rice also dropped by 850,000 hectares,
or 11.1 percent to 6.8 million hectares.
</P>
<P>
Since the Chinese government scrapped protective prices for
surplus and poor quality spring rice and wheat, market prices have
been spiraling down, forcing grain growers to shift to other crops
that will bring in higher economic returns. The most severe
drought in a decade this spring also disrupted sowing in many
places.
</P>
<P>
Planting areas of sugar plants dropped by 142,000 hectares to 1.
276 million hectares, while jute decreased by 14,000 hectares to
34,000 hectares.
</P>
<P>
This shows that Chinese farmers are increasingly responsive to
market demands and more ready to adjust crops mix in line with
government policy.
</P>
<P>
Planting areas of cotton continued to recover this spring due
to market optimism and China's pending accession to the WTO.
</P>
<P>
Some 3.524 million hectares of cotton have been planted, 59,000
hectares, or 1.7 percent more than in last year.
</P>
<P>
Planting areas of tobacco also grew by 33,000 hectares to 973,
000 hectares as more farmers shifted from grain growing to cash
crops. 
</P>
</TEXT>
