<DOCNO> XIE20000629.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Daily Air Quality Report for 42 Chinese Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Shijiazhuang, Taiyuan, Lanzhou and
Urumqi in north and northwest China reported slightly polluted air
today.
</P>
<P>
According to the daily air quality report issued by the China
Environmental Monitoring Center today, fairly good air was
reported in 26 cities. They are Beijing, Tianjin, Hohhot, Shenyang,
Changchun, Harbin, Shanghai, Nanjing, Suzhou, Nantong, Hangzhou,
Wenzhou, Fuzhou, Nanchang, Jinan, Yantai, Zhengzhou, Wuhan,
Changsha, Guangzhou, Nanning, Chengdu, Guiyang, Xi'an, Xining and
Yinchuan.
</P>
<P>
All the 30 aforementioned cities, except Nanning and Guiyang,
listed particulates less than 10 microns in size as their major
pollutants while sulfur dioxide is the major air pollutants in
Nanning and Guiyang.
</P>
<P>
Dalian, Hefei, Xiamen, Qingdao, Shenzhen, Zhuhai, Shantou,
Zhanjiang, Haikou, Chongqing, Kunming and Lhasa reported excellent
air.
</P>
<P>
The center classifies air quality in China's urban areas into
five levels: level-one or excellent (pollution indexes below 50),
level-two or fairly good (pollution indexes ranging from 51 to 100)
, level-three or slightly polluted (pollution indexes ranging from
101-200), level-four or poor (pollution indexes ranging from 201
to 300) and level-five or hazardous (pollution indexes over 301).
</P>
<P>
The 42 cities monitored include the four municipalities of
Beijing, Tianjin, Shanghai and Chongqing, provincial capitals, and
major cities in economically developed coastal areas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
