<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Releases 450 Iraqi POWs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Iran Wednesday night freed 450 Iraqi
prisoners of war (POWs), 12 years after a bloody war between the
two countries ended.
</P>
<P>
The POWs were released on the border spot of Khosrawi in the
western Kermanshah Province, the Islamic Republic News Agency
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
With the release of this batch of POWs, Iran has freed a total
of 3,389 Iraqi POWs since the beginning of the current Iranian year
(which started March 20), said Asghar Azizi, head of Iran's POW
commission.
</P>
<P>
He said the release ceremony was attended by representatives of
the International Committee of the Red Cross, which since the end
of the Iran-Iraq war in 1988 has supervised repatriations of almost
98,000 POWs from both sides.
</P>
<P>
The fate of thousands of captives is among the thorniest issues
hindering the improvement of ties between the two neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Iran says it has documents showing more than 3,000 Iranian POWs
are still being held in Iraq, while Baghdad maintains Iran is still
holding thousands of its soldiers.
</P>
<P>
The eight-year war has claimed the lives of some 1 million
people and severely damaged the two countries' economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
