<HEADLINE> Islamic Nations Need to Take Stock of Themselves: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"We need to see why and where our shortfalls are, what needs to
be done to bring the Islamic World closer and how should it be
done,"he said at the opening of the Global Muslim Showcase 2000
Malaysia from June 29 to July 2 held in conduction with the
ongoing 27th Islamic Conference of Foreign Ministers (ICFM) here.
</P>
<P>
He said the first step is to have the will and sincere desire
to synergize efforts for building and developing the Islamic world
and this should be followed by bridging the wide information gap
existing among the Islamic countries.
</P>
<P>
Once the information on what each Islamic country has to offer
and its needs, with regards to exports, imports, investments,
transfer of technology, know-how and others are bridged, the
countries would be in a better position to know that their needs
could be fulfilled from within the Islamic world, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said there is no reason as to why Islamic nations could not
collectively be a challenging force as they do not lack anything,
being rich in resources, manpower, experience and know how.
</P>
<P>
The four-day (ICFM) meeting opened here Tuesday. 
