<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Sets Export Target for 2000-2001 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan has set a 10-billion-U.
S.-dollar export target for the fiscal year 2000-2001, marking an
11 percent increase over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by Commerce Minister Abdul Razzak Dawood on
the state electronic media Wednesday evening while releasing the
government's new year trade policy.
</P>
<P>
According to the new trade policy, while enhancing market share
of the country's top 10 textile and non-textile categories, the
greater emphasis is on value addition and capturing the world
market share of non-traditional items.
</P>
<P>
Dawood said that in the non-traditional items the trade policy
will focus on software, engineering goods, chemicals, fruits and
vegetables.
</P>
<P>
In all, the trade policy is banked on export of textiles, wheat,
rice, fruits and vegetables, gems and jewelry, software leather
and garments.
</P>
<P>
To enhance the quantity as well as the quality of exports, a
Skill Development Council is to be set up, which will function as
an umbrella organization for the existing institutes and also
develop new ones.
</P>
<P>
An Export Facilitation Union will also be set up in the Central
Bureau of Revenue together with the setting-up of a Product Up-
gradation and Market Development Fund, all for the promotion of
foreign trade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
