<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Records Growth in Industrial Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The exports which contributed most to the export earnings were
food items, beverages and tobacco, textiles and apparels,
petroleum products, leather and rubber, a Central Bank official
told the newspaper Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The earnings from food, beverages and tobacco recorded 44.14
million dollars, petroleum products 30.34 million dollars, leather
and rubber 131.03 million dollars and other earnings 151.72
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The textile and garment exports have contributed largely
throughout to industrial export earnings. The export earning last
year stood at 4,600 million U.S. dollars which was 4 percent below
the previous year's earnings due to low commodity prices that
prevailed in the world market, he said.
</P>
<P>
Competition from East Asian countries also contributed to the
low prices of the major export products, textiles and garments,
said the official, adding that natural rubber and rubber products
too were affected for the same reason. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
