<DOCNO> XIE20000629.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Polish President to Visit Moscow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Polish President Aleksander
Kwasniewski will pay a working visit to Moscow and meet his
Russian counterpart Vladimir Putin on July 10, the presidential
office announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral relations have been strained since Poland joined NATO
in March 1999 and deteriorated early this year by Poland's
expulsion of nine Russian diplomats accused of spying and the
attack on the Russian consulate by pro-Chechen protesters in
Poznan, Poland.
</P>
<P>
Putin said at the end of last year that he would visit Poland
this spring but the plan was shelved following the two incidents.
</P>
<P>
The coming visit by Kwasniewski sends another signal that
leaders of the two countries hope to heal their cooled relations.
</P>
<P>
On March 6, Kwasniewski called the then Acting President Putin
and thanked him for the liberation of two Polish women scientists
from Chechen captivity.
</P>
<P>
Following Putin's victory in presidential election on March 26
both countries have repeatedly stated their desire to improve
relations.
</P>
<P>
In a telephone conversation on March 29, Kwasniewski
congratulated Putin on his victory and invited him to visit Poland.
</P>
<P>
On April 12, Putin called his Polish counterpart and both
presidents said they will improve bilateral relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
