<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Intel Launches Pentium IV Computer Chip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Industry analysts believed that the Pentium IV far outpaces the
processing power of Athlon chip running at 1 billion bits of
information per second, recently announced by rival Advanced
Micro Devices Inc. (AMD).
</P>
<P>
Computers operating at such speeds are essential in a world
where new generations of Internet commerce, gaming and
entertainment require greater processing power, Intel's chief
executive, Craig Barrett, said while unveiling the new name at
Intel's Santa Clara, Calif., headquarters.
</P>
<P>
Intel's fastest chip until now has been a Pentium III that
processes information at 850 megahertz, slightly more than half as
fast as the new Pentium IV.
</P>
<P>
The Pentium IV will be introduced in the second half of this
year and is aimed at offering faster performance, as well as
enhanced graphics, video and other capabilities.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts said consumers should wait until software
developers catch up with chipmakers before spending additional
money on computers using such high-performance chips as the
Pentium IV.
</P>
<P>
Eventually, as Intel moves Pentium IV down market, into mid-
range PCs, it will replace the Pentium III as the company's main
volume chip, according to other analysts who also predict the
Pentium III will be around for some time, lasting into 2002 in
mobile applications.
</P>
<P>
Compared to the Pentium III, Pentium IV is tuned for much
higher clock speed performance. At the same time, it also offers a
wider 400 MHz system bus, the pipeline that connects the chip to
memory and other system components. The current Intel standard is
133 MHz now offered with the Pentium III chip. Pentium IV will
also have a larger on-chip cache, which will help improve
performance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
