<HEADLINE> Georgia to Reduce 9,000 Army Servicemen in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 28 (Xinhua) -- The Georgian parliament Wednesday
passed a bill on cutting down the national armed forces from 47,
500 to 38,400 servicemen by the end of this year, reported the
Interfax news agency.
</P>
<P>
Before the voting at a plenary session of the legislature in
Tbilisi, Revaz Adamiya, chairman of the parliamentary committee
for national defense and security, said the reduction has become
necessary as a radical reform is being carried out in the defense
sector recently.
</P>
<P>
The reform aims to modernize the army of the former Soviet
republic to meet the military standards of the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization (NATO) to pave the way for gaining a full NATO
membership by 2005, he said.
</P>
<P>
The reduction will mainly focus on cutting down logistic
personnel. The staff of the combat units will remain unchanged.
Under the reform, Georgia's armed force will be further cut down
to 13,000 or even 12,000 people by 2004, said Georgian First
Deputy Defense Minister Zhoni Pirtskhalaishvily.
</P>
<P>
The Georgian government cannot afford the existing scale of
defense sector owing to the budget crisis, observers said. And
worse still, the servicemen of the Georgian army have not received
their pay for 14 months, according to the parliamentary opposition.
</P>
<P>
Georgia's defense budget is reportedly no more than 20 million
U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
