<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Kosovo ethnic Albanians staged
their first demonstration against the KFOR international
peacekeeping force to protest against the destruction of a huge
arms stash belonging to former rebels, KFOR official said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The crowd up to 1,000 ethnic Albanians used trucks to block the
way into the village of Lapusnik late Tuesday and waved banners
saying "KFOR out of Kosovo" and "These weapons belong to the
Albanian people," said the KFOR spokesman, who was quoted by the
Yugoslav news agency Tanjug.
</P>
<P>
He said it was the first time ethnic Albanians have
demonstrated against KFOR since the NATO-led force was stationed
in Kosovo last year, and added that the rally was certainly well-
organized.
</P>
<P>
KFOR troops found four bunkers filled with weapons and
explosives, which belonged to the former Kosovo Liberation Army (
KLA), earlier this month in the central village of Klecki. A huge
amount of them were later destroyed.
</P>
<P>
Under U.N. Resolution 1244, which was not well implemented, the
KLA should have been disbanded by last September. They have only
turned in a small amount of their weapons so far. 
</P>
