<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Online PC Sales to Increase Rapidly in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 28 (Xinhua) -- The number of personal
computers (PC) U.S. consumers purchase online will increase
rapidly over the next five years, an American market research firm
predicted Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to International Data Corporation (IDC), just eight
percent of all PCs were sold to U.S. consumers, or fewer than 1.4
million sets, via the Internet in 1999. In 2004, close to 40
percent of all consumer PC sales in the United States or almost 9.
3 million sets, will be made online.
</P>
<P>
The IDC estimates 50 percent of U.S. homes owned at least one
PC last year and almost 36 percent have Internet access. "Given
the current penetration of PCs in the home and the rapid rise in
the percentage of home accessing the Internet, a greater number of
consumers will utilize the Web as a commerce tool when shopping
for a new PC," the IDC said.
</P>
<P>
Targeted marketing efforts, convenience, growing comfort with e-
commerce and price will all help to drive consumer PC sales over
the Internet, the IDC said. But PC manufacturers would have to
rely on Internet channel partners rather than relying on direct
sales online.
</P>
<P>
According to the IDC, the most successful computer sellers will
be those that offer a combination of online and brick-and-mortar
sales. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
