BAGHDAD -- A spokesman of the United Nations Food and
Agriculture Organization (FAO) has confirmed two employees of the
U.N. organization were killed by a gunman in the Iraqi capital
Baghdad early Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that at 8:30 local time (0430 GMT), a lone
gunman burst into the office building of the U.N. organization in
Baghdad, and exchanged fire with government guards at the building.
(Iraq-FAO-Murder)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MANILA -- Fourteen persons, including an Army colonel, were
killed Tuesday afternoon by suspected leftist rebels in Isabela
province in the northern Philippines while on the way to their
camp from a medical mission, a TV report said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the ABS-CBN television, Colonel Josefino Manayao,
commander of the fifth Infantry Division's 502nd Infantry Brigade,
was heading the convoy when a group of armed men sprayed with
bullets the tail-end of the troop's military truck around 2 p.m.
Tuesday. (Philippines-Ambush)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Republican leaders of the U.S. House of
Representatives on Tuesday reached an agreement to allow direct
sales of U.S. food and medicine to Cuba for the first time in
nearly four decades.
</P>
<P>
The deal, which was reached after more than five hours of
overnight negotiations, would clear the way for congressional
approval of calls by U.S. farm and business groups to exempt food
and medicine from unilateral embargoes. (US-Cuba-Sanctions)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- Mexican police have seized 4.3 tons of marihuana
hidden under ice-cream and mangos, said the Office of the Attorney
General Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the office said the drugs were discovered during
routine inspections of a truck in a highway of the country's
northwestern state of Baja California. (Mexico-Drug)  
</P>
