<HEADLINE> Norman Crashed as Seeds Scattered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Belgian qualifier Olivier Rochus
produced the day's biggest surprise at the Wimbledon on Wednesday
when he defeated world number two Magnus Norman in five sets.
</P>
<P>
The 19-year-old sent the Swede into a total frustration in the
match, in which he lost 6-4, 2-6, 6-4, 6-7 and 6-1.
</P>
<P>
The Swede, playing his 55th match of the year, was so
dispirited by the penultimate game of the defeat that he asked a
ball girl to play a rally for him.
</P>
<P>
Seven men's seeds have now fallen in the first three days of
the championships - six of them in the top half of the draw which
means defending champion Pete Sampras has only one seed,Thomas
Enqvist of Sweden, between him and the final.
</P>
<P>
Sampras, going for a record 13th Grand Slam title, beat
Slovakia's Karol Kucera 7-6, 3-6, 6-3, 6-4 in failing light on
Center Court after having his left ankle strapped heavily in the
third set.
</P>
<P>
The 28-year-old American was taken to hospital after the match
where his inflamed foot was given a scan. His injury will be "re-
evaluated" on Thursday morning, organisers said.
</P>
<P>
Martina Navratilova, away from the All England Club for five
years since her retirement, returned to partner Mariaan de Swardt
to a 6-3, 6-7, 6-3 victory over Amanda Hopmans and Lubomira
Bacheva in the first round of the women's doubles.
</P>
<P>
The nine-times singles champion played as though she had never
been away as she took her first step towards a record-equalling
20th Wimbledon title, aged 43. 
</P>
</TEXT>
