<DOCNO> XIE20000629.0295 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: New Change on Zimbabwe's Political Arena </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
By Zhu Shixiang
</P>
<P>
HARARE, June 28 (Xinhua) -- A big change has taken place in the
 Zimbabwean political arena with a new opposition party posing a
threat to the 20-year-domination of the ruling party.
</P>
<P>
In the fifth parliamentary election on June 24-25, the ruling
Zimbabwe African National Union-Patriotic Front (Zanu-pf) won
narrowly with 62 seats against 57 seats for the Movement for
Democratic Change, which was formed nine months ago. It was the
first time the ruling party lost many seats to a opposition party.
</P>
<P>
From the country's independence in 1980, Zanu-pf, which fought
a bitter war against British colonialists, had enjoyed support
from the majority of people due to its efforts in improving its
peoples' lives by building schools and hospitals, providing free
primary education and creating new jobs.
</P>
<P>
In the just-ended election, Zanu-pf still had massive backing
from people in the rural areas, but lost heavily in towns because
of the difficult economic situation greatly affecting urban
residents.
</P>
<P>
But, when the International Monetary Fund and the World Bank
demanded Zimbabwe to introduce economic structural adjustment
program in the early 1990s, the hard economic times were triggered
off. Unemployment soared. Interest rates shot up. Foreign
investment flowed out of the country. The prices of basic
commodities, such as bread and cooking oil, rose dramatically.
</P>
<P>
Many people, especially those in towns, began to complain that
Zanu-pf had forgotten them.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwe Congress of Trade Unions (ZCTU) took advantage of
the situation and launched the new party, the Movement for
Democratic Change, which turned out to be "a black horse" in the
parliamentary election.
</P>
<P>
With the backing of the working class, MDC challenged the once
unchallenged Zanu-pf and reaped its first victory when it
mobilized supporters to vote against the proposed constitutional
reform draft during the referendum in February this year.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the MDC has surged ahead with bold confidence.
</P>
<P>
When President Robert Mugabe announced that the election would
be held in June this year, MDC made it clear that it would field
candidates for all the 120 contested seats. The MDC did give
Zanu-pf a hard time during the parliamentary election.
</P>
<P>
However, Zanu-pf is still in control of the parliament since
President Mugabe is empowered by the constitution to appoint 30
people to Parliament. This allows Mugabe to form a government
merely from his Zanu-pf.
</P>
<P>
But political observers have urged him to form a coalition
government which he did with Zimbabwe African People Union (Zapu)
at independence in 1980.
</P>
<P>
After the marginal victory in the parliamentary election, the
government is faced with the big job of reversing the slowdown of
the economy.
</P>
<P>
But the pressing issue that the Zanu-pf should tackle is land
distribution. Only 4,500 whites own 70 percent of fertile land
while more than 12 million people are still living on very poor
soils in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Just before the election, the freedom fighters, who fought for
 independence, occupied about 1,500 farms owned by whites, saying
Zanu-pf was taking too long in getting back the land from British
settlers.
</P>
<P>
These veterans have vowed to remain on the occupied farms until
the government buys enough farms to settle them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000629.0296 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: New Change on Zimbabwe's Political Arena </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
By Zhu Shixiang
</P>
<P>
HARARE, June 28 (Xinhua) -- A big change has taken place in the
 Zimbabwean political arena with a new opposition party posing a
threat to the 20-year-domination of the ruling party.
</P>
<P>
In the fifth parliamentary election on June 24-25, the ruling
Zimbabwe African National Union-Patriotic Front (Zanu-pf) won
narrowly with 62 seats against 57 seats for the Movement for
Democratic Change, which was formed nine months ago. It was the
first time the ruling party lost many seats to a opposition party.
</P>
<P>
From the country's independence in 1980, Zanu-pf, which fought
a bitter war against British colonialists, had enjoyed support
from the majority of people due to its efforts in improving its
peoples' lives by building schools and hospitals, providing free
primary education and creating new jobs.
</P>
<P>
In the just-ended election, Zanu-pf still had massive backing
from people in the rural areas, but lost heavily in towns because
of the difficult economic situation greatly affecting urban
residents.
</P>
<P>
But, when the International Monetary Fund and the World Bank
demanded Zimbabwe to introduce economic structural adjustment
program in the early 1990s, the hard economic times were triggered
off. Unemployment soared. Interest rates shot up. Foreign
investment flowed out of the country. The prices of basic
commodities, such as bread and cooking oil, rose dramatically.
</P>
<P>
Many people, especially those in towns, began to complain that
Zanu-pf had forgotten them.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwe Congress of Trade Unions (ZCTU) took advantage of
the situation and launched the new party, the Movement for
Democratic Change, which turned out to be "a black horse" in the
parliamentary election.
</P>
<P>
With the backing of the working class, MDC challenged the once
unchallenged Zanu-pf and reaped its first victory when it
mobilized supporters to vote against the proposed constitutional
reform draft during the referendum in February this year.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the MDC has surged ahead with bold confidence.
</P>
<P>
When President Robert Mugabe announced that the election would
be held in June this year, MDC made it clear that it would field
candidates for all the 120 contested seats. The MDC did give
Zanu-pf a hard time during the parliamentary election.
</P>
<P>
However, Zanu-pf is still in control of the parliament since
President Mugabe is empowered by the constitution to appoint 30
people to Parliament. This allows Mugabe to form a government
merely from his Zanu-pf.
</P>
<P>
But political observers have urged him to form a coalition
government which he did with Zimbabwe African People Union (Zapu)
at independence in 1980.
</P>
<P>
After the marginal victory in the parliamentary election, the
government is faced with the big job of reversing the slowdown of
the economy.
</P>
<P>
But the pressing issue that the Zanu-pf should tackle is land
distribution. Only 4,500 whites own 70 percent of fertile land
while more than 12 million people are still living on very poor
soils in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Just before the election, the freedom fighters, who fought for
 independence, occupied about 1,500 farms owned by whites, saying
Zanu-pf was taking too long in getting back the land from British
settlers.
</P>
<P>
These veterans have vowed to remain on the occupied farms until
the government buys enough farms to settle them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
