<HEADLINE> NIgerian Government to Mediate Lagos Workers' Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 28 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian federal government will
mediate the trade dispute between the Lagos state government and
workers, who embarked on a strike here seven days ago over the
minimum wage, the News Agency of Nigeria reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
As both sides to the dispute remain entrenched in their
positions, the Federal Ministry of Employment, Labor and
Productivity is expected to refer the dispute to the Industrial
Arbitration Panel (IAP), according to the news agency.
</P>
<P>
"This means that the strike has to be called off and the state
 government must also cease to lock out workers," a source in the
ministry said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The state governor, Bola Tinubu, has in the meantime directed
an immediate resumption of the negotiation between the government
and the workers.
</P>
<P>
State lawmakers have advised the government to withdraw a suit
against the workers at a Lagos High Court, and the workers to call
off the strike.
</P>
<P>
The workers embarked on the strike Thursday to pressure the
government to pay them a monthly minimum wage of 7,500 naira as
against 5,500 naira offered by the state government (about 100
naira is equal to one U. S. dollar). 
</P>
</TEXT>
