<HEADLINE> U.S. Maintains Dominance Over L. American Poultry Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The United States has a dominating
position in the Latin American poultry market and damages the
producers, Latin America Poultry Producers Association (ALA)
chairman Fernando Ikeda Matsukawa said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Ikeda said in Lima that being a big producer, the United States
exports the surplus of its national consumption at very low prices,
damaging the poultry activity in the zone.
</P>
<P>
"The countries of all the region are getting together to demand
fairness, and we think that this is an abuse of dominance by the
United States," said the Peruvian businessman, also manager of the
San Fernando poultry enterprise.
</P>
<P>
The ALA representative announced that the regional organization
is preparing the documents to file a demand before the World Trade
Organization (WTO) to solve this problem.
</P>
<P>
"It is estimated that the negotiations for the Free Trade Area
of the Americas (FTAA) establishment will start in April of 2001,
so we still have time to present the documents to support our
position," said Ikeda.
</P>
<P>
Ikeda said that the unfair competition made the first five
months of this year difficult for the poultry industry enterprises.
</P>
</TEXT>
