<HEADLINE> Chretien Unveils 700 Mln C. Dlrs for Atlantic Canada Strategy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Prime Minister Jean
Chretien unveiled an Atlantic Canada strategy of 700 million
Canadian dollars (about 473 million U.S. dollars) Thursday to
narrow the region's development gap with the rest of the country.
</P>
<P>
Chretien told a press conference in Halifax, Nova Scotia, that
the five-year funding in the form of Atlantic Investment
Partnership came at the time when "Atlantic Canada's economy is
changing."
</P>
<P>
"The traditional resource dependent economy is becoming more
knowledge-intensive. And economic growth is being driven more and
more by innovation, technology, tourism and exports," said the
prime minister.
</P>
<P>
"Atlantic Canada has lower levels of productivity and less
investment in research and development. It does not export as much
as other regions of Canada. And unemployment is still too high,"
according to the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
A flagship initiative to narrow that development gap is an
Atlantic Investment Fund of 300 million Canadian dollars (about
203 million U.S. dollars), which will be used to build technology
and research facilities, ranging from universities to institutes.
</P>
<P>
Two of the other initiatives include the Partnership for
Community Economic Development and the Partnership for Trade and
Investment.
</P>
<P>
Atlantic Canada is composed of the country's eastern provinces
of Nova Scotia, New Brunswick, Prince Edward Island and
Newfoundland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
