<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Telecoms Send Major European Stocks Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
London's benchmark FTSE 100 closed down 74.5 points at 6239,
continuing a run that has seen it lose nearly 300 points courtesy
of falls in six of the last seven sessions.
</P>
<P>
Microchip designer ARM Holdings was the top loser on the index,
down 9.7 percent as investors reassessed valuations of
semiconductor-related companies that have counted on positive
forecasts of the growth in chip demand that the mobile-phone
industry is expected to generate.
</P>
<P>
Also downtrodden in the sector: network operator Energis,
slipping 9.6 percent, telecom equipment maker Marconi, down 7.3
percent, and telephone service provider Cable &AMP; Wireless shedding
6.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Cable company Telewest Communications slid 7.1 percent,
following an announcement it would sell 450 million US dollars of
convertible bonds.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE Eurotop 300 sand 2.2 percent, with its technology
hardware sub-index tumbling 8.9 percent behind the declines for
Ericsson and Nokia. Its telecom component fell 5.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
German technology and telecoms shares tumbled, led by DAX
heavyweight Deutsche Telekom which closed down more than seven
percent. The index ended 181.51 or 2.57 percent lower at 6874.54
points.
</P>
<P>
The CAC 40 in Paris tumbled 207.14 points, or 3.1 percent, to
6400.82, with the top 6 percentage losers in the "new economy"
sectors of technology, media and telecommunications. 
</P>
