<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece Not Optimistic Over New Round of Cyprus Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
ATHENS, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Greece was not optimistic over the
result of the forthcoming U.N.-sponsored talks between Cyprus' two
communities in Geneva on July 5.
</P>
<P>
"I would say that nobody can talk about optimism. We cannot
have high expectations because of the completely negative attitude
of the other (Turkish) side," Greek government spokesman Dimitris
Reppas said at a press briefing Thursday.
</P>
<P>
To reunite the divided island, the Greek Cypriot side led by
President Glafcos Clerides and the Turkish Cypriot side led Rauf
Denktash have held two rounds of indirect talks in New York and
Geneva respectively, and the third round of such talks is expected
to take place in Geneva on July 5, but Denktash had been
threatening not to go to Geneva because of the non-inclusion of an
addendum in the U.N. secretary general's report with a Turkish
Cypriot demand for separate consultations with the U.N. Peace-
Keeping Force in Cyprus (UNFICYP).
</P>
<P>
Reppas said that they should show the international community
that the Turkish side was the one to blame for the deadlock in
efforts for a settlement of the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus President Clerides will visit Greece next Monday to
discuss with Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis the Geneva talks
he will have with Denktash.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that Clerides' talks with Simitis would be
substantive.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriots-controlled
south and the Turkish Cypriots-dominated north since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed coup seeking union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
Greece, which has signed a joint defense agreement with Cyprus,
and Cyprus support the reunification of the island in a federation
formula in line with the U.N. resolutions while Turkey and the
Turkish Cypriot side demand that a confederation formed by two
sovereign states be set up on the Mediterranean island. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
