<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuba To Honor Migratory Accords with U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The Cuban government announced
Thursday that it will continue honoring the migratory agreements
signed with the United States.
</P>
<P>
Cuba is also willing to resume talks on the theme "when
conditions will permit it."
</P>
<P>
Cuban Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Aymee Hernandez said at her
press conference that "Cuba continues committed to the strict
compliance with the migratory agreements signed with the United
States."
</P>
<P>
Washington and Havana have an agreement in force since May of
1995 that seeks to facilitate a legal, ordered and safe emigration.
</P>
<P>
The spokeswoman said that when conditions are adequate, her
country will be willing to resume the migratory talks with the
United States, which had been scheduled for June 16-29 in New York,
but were suspended by Havana 10 days ago.
</P>
<P>
Hernandez said that when Cuba announced the suspension of the
talks, it had said that the conditions were not adequate not only
because Elian Gonzalez was in the United States, but because there
are other discrepancies.
</P>
<P>
Elian returned Wednesday to Havana after nine months of
retention in the United States, after surviving a wreckage of
illegal emigrants, in which his mother and stepfather drowned.
</P>
<P>
The spokeswoman mentioned among the discrepancies between
Washington and Havana the Law of Cuban Adjustment and the
propaganda of radio stations, which encourage from Florida the
illegal emigration of Cubans.
</P>
<P>
The Cuban Adjustment Act in force since 1966 permits Cuban
emigrants who illegally set foot on U.S. soil to obtain residence
and work permits, which has been denounced by the Cuban
authorities as a tacit encouragement to illegal emigration.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
