<HEADLINE> Blair: Britain Wants to Join Euro Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BERLIN, June 29 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
Thursday said his country would take part in the euro zone, but
would do so only if "the economic tests were pleasing."
</P>
<P>
Blair, who arrived in Germany on a working visit, discussed
the future of Europe with German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder in
the evening in Potsdam near Berlin.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders held private talks focusing on French
President Jacques Chirac's proposals for a "European basic law
framework" and for a "pioneer group" in European integration.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, Chirac gave a speech at the German
parliament urging Germany and France to lead deeper integration by
some member states.
</P>
<P>
Blair said he agreed with France on a "common European basic
law framework," and Britain should be afraid of being excluded
from the European integration.
</P>
<P>
Chirac's speech is "not talking about a hardcore Europe, but
talking about expanded cooperation. There is no reason at all why
we should be sensitive about this," said Blair.
</P>
<P>
"We should be a full player in Europe," he stressed, adding
that Britain was interested in docking with the euro successfully.
That was important for Britain's job market, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
