<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Business Leaders Call for Senate Action on PNTR in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 29 (Xinhua) -- U.S. business leaders Thursday
again called on the Senate to vote in July on the bill granting
permanent normal trade relations (PNTR) status to China.
</P>
<P>
"If PNTR is lost ... America will pay the consequences for
decades," said Thomas Donohua, president of the U.S. Chamber of
Commerce, in a joint statement.
</P>
<P>
The joint statement was issued by the U.S. Chamber of Commerce,
the National Association of Manufacturers, the Business Roundtable,
and the Information Technology Industry Council.
</P>
<P>
The statement urged Senate Republican Leader Trent Lott to
schedule a final vote in July on a the PNTR bill, warning that a
delay of vote could hurt the interests of American companies and
cause a set-back for U.S.-China relations.
</P>
<P>
"PNTR is an essential national priority, not just for economic
reasons, but because it will set the stage for U.S.-China
relations in the decades to come," said Samuel Maury, president of
the Business Roundtable.
</P>
<P>
"It is important enough not to be delayed," he said. "If PNTR
is deferred much longer, we may squander a historic opportunity to
set U.S.-China relations on a positive course for the 21st century.
"
</P>
<P>
"We urge the Senate leadership to set a firm date in July for
the vote on PNTR," said Jerry J. Jasinowski, president of the
National Association of Manufacturers. "We believe there is a
strong, bipartisan support for PNTR in the Senate and there is no
reason to wait any longer to move this historic legislation
forward."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. House of Representatives passed the PNTR bill by a
vote of 237-197 on May 24.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. business community hoped that the House-passed bill
will give American companies long-sought access to China markets.
</P>
<P>
Trent Lott of Mississippi said earlier this month that he
expects the Senate to vote on the PNTR bill in July, but he has
not set a specific date yet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
