<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The Liberian government Thursday
announced the release of 21 Indian U.N. peacekeepers who had been
trapped by rebels in neighboring Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Liberian Information Minister Joe Mulbah said that the group
was now at a Liberian border town and expected in the Liberian
capital Monrovia shortly, according to reports reaching here from
Monrovia.
</P>
<P>
The minister said Liberia hoped the release would lead to a
negotiated solution to the war in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
About 200 peacekeepers are thought to be still surrounded by
the Revolutionary United Front (RUF) rebels in the east.
</P>
<P>
Mulbah said earlier that the peacekeepers, including a senior
British military observer, should all be released by the weekend.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the Liberian president had recently received
envoys from the United Nations and India, who asked him to solve
the crisis.
</P>
<P>
He said the imminent release of the remaining peacekeepers was
part of a deal under which the Sierra Leone rebels have been
promised a ceasefire and a return to the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
The RUF rebels originally took hostage about 500 U.N.
peacekeepers in May. 
</P>
