<HEADLINE> Argentines To Sue U.K. for Malvinas War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The relatives of Argentine
sailors who died in the sinking of the General Belgrano cruiser by
a British submarine during the 1982 Malvinas War will sue the
United Kingdom for damages.
</P>
<P>
One of the lawyers said Thursday that the relatives of two of
the 323 sailors killed in the sinking will present Tuesday the
case before the Strasbourg, France, Human Rights International
Court.
</P>
<P>
The denunciation will be directed to the British government, in
the person of former Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher and her war
cabinet, for the violation of the right to life.
</P>
<P>
The accusation says that according to the law applied in armed
conflicts, the goal of the belligerents is to put the enemy out of
combat, but it must not constitute any danger for the belligerent.
</P>
<P>
It says that the sinking was out of the theater of war
operations and of the zone of exclusion established by the United
Kingdom, violating the conventions established for wartime in The
Hague in 1907.
</P>
<P>
The denunciation says that at no moment the Argentine cruiser
entered the zone of exclusion, but that on the contrary, in the
early hours of that day it moved in the direction of the Isla de
los Estados, completely opposed to the war operations scenario.
</P>
<P>
The Argentine cruiser General Belgrano was sunk on May 2, 1982,
with 1,093 men aboard, by torpedoes launched by the British
submarine Conqueror, 36 nautical miles out of the exclusion zone
of 200 miles established by Britain around the Malvina Islands.
</P>
<P>
The cruiser that was sunk was at the moment of the attack at
some south latitude of 55 degrees 24 minutes and west longitude of
61 degrees 32 minutes, meaning 91 miles from the Argentine coasts
of the Isla de los Estados, and out of the 200 mile zone around
the Malvinas Islands Georgia del Sur and Sandwich del Sur.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
