<HEADLINE> Russian Police Detain 75 New Fascists in Moscow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The Russian police arrested 75 new
fascists making trouble at the Savyolovsky Park in central Moscow
Wednesday evening, reported Russian news agencies Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The incident took place at around 21:20 Moscow time (1820 GMT)
Wednesday when a group of about 100 young skinheads giving Nazi-
style salutes gathered near a disco bar in the downtown park after
a rock concert and got into affray and fights, the Moscow Main
Internal Affairs Department told reporters Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The patrol police of the district, who arrived at the scene at
alarm, became the targets of hurled stones and bottles. One
policeman was injured during the clashes, said the police.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses said at least four cars were badly damaged, one with
blood spattered on the bonnet.
</P>
<P>
The police had to draw their weapons and fire several warning
fires into the air but failed to stop them. The group then surged
into adjoining areas where they were confronted by riot police
reinforcements dispatched to the scene. The crowd was frightened
and tried to flee, but 75 of them were seized.
</P>
<P>
Extreme right-wing groups have a measure of influence among
some groups of disaffected young people in turbulent post-Soviet
Russia. Interest in many groups focuses on cult rock groups, some
performing in Nazi regalia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
