<HEADLINE> Mexico To Get More Oil Income This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, June 29 (Xinhua) -- High oil prices could give
Mexico additional income close to three billion U.S. dollars this
year, said Jose Antonio Rojas Nieto, a professor at the National
Autonomous University of Mexico (UNAM).
</P>
<P>
Rojas said that if the volume of exports and a quotation of
around 22 dollars per barrel are maintained, the Mexican
authorities will obtain big profits with their crude exports, the
El Financiero newspaper said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
This can be attributed to the fact that the income from exports
could surpass that of 1999 when 8.859 billion dollars were
received as the result of a daily average sale of crude abroad of
1.553 million barrels a day (bpd), said Rojas.
</P>
<P>
The analyst said that by the end of this year, if an average of
exports similar to last year's is maintained, with a price of 22
dollars per barrel, income for 13 billion dollars, could be
obtained, meaning 1.117 billion dollars more than the programmed.
</P>
<P>
Mexico is not member of the Organization of the Petroleum
Exporting Countries (OPEC), but one of the main producers and
exporters in the world.
</P>
<P>
Mexico produced three million barrels of oil a day during the
first five months of 2000, according to a Petroleos Mexicanos (
Pemex) bulletin.
</P>
<P>
Pemex, the state-owned oil company, earned 5.786 billion
dollars from crude exports in the first five months of this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
