<HEADLINE> Mexico, Northern Triangle Sign Free Trade Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Presidents from Mexico,
Guatemala and El Salvador and the vice president of Honduras
signed Thursday in this capital the Mexico-Northern Triangle Free
Trade Agreement, with the presidents of Costa Rica, Nicaragua, and
Panama as witnesses.
</P>
<P>
The leaders underscored during the signing ceremony held at
Chapultepec Castle in Mexico City the importance of this agreement
for the strengthening of the peace and the development of the
signing countries, and also for the regional integration.
</P>
<P>
Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo said that the agreement "is a
firm step toward the real Latin American integration that will
always respect the sovereignty and the identity of each nation."
</P>
<P>
The historic ceremony was attended as witnesses by Nicaraguan
President Arnoldo Aleman, Costa Rican President Miguel Angel
Rodriguez and Panamanian President Mireya Moscoso.
</P>
<P>
The Mexico-Northern Triangle Free Trade Agreement that will
open a potential market of 124 million consumers will go into
force on January 1, 2001, after it is approved by the legislative
assembly of each country.
</P>
<P>
This agreement opens the possibility for the four countries to
increase their trade and investments and will contribute to
economic development and the creation of jobs and will attract
investments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
